<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Takes Delivery of U.S.-Made Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Sunday took delivery
of five U.S.-made ground-to-ground Atacams missiles, the first
consignment of a 19-billion drachma (about 633 million U.S.
dollars) order for 40 of such missiles.
</P>
<P>
The all-weather missiles, which have a range of 165 kilometers,
were delivered at the Sedes military airport in the northern Greek
city of Thessaloniki, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a delivery ceremony, Greece's Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said that the government's goal was to build a
strong, modern army and an all-powerful deterrent and defense
force for the country's sovereignty, which would also support
Greece's peaceful and creative role in the wider geopolitical
region.
</P>
<P>
The missiles, which can be launched from mobile M270 units, are
reportedly designed to hit high-priority targets including
administrative and control installations and munitions depots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
