<HEADLINE> Taliban Rejects Iran's Request for Apology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 13 (Xinhua)-- The Islamic Taliban militia
Sunday rejected Iran's request for tendering an apology and
handing over the killers of nine Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
"We will never tender apology to Iran for the killing of its
diplomats as the Afghan Islamic Emirate is not involved in the
incident," Taliban's envoy in Pakistan, Saeedur Rahman Haqqani
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Iranian diplomats and one reporter went missing when the
Taliban fighters took over the Afghan northern city of
Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the pro-Iranian northern alliance,
early last month.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have been denying Iran's allegations of
abducting these Iranians, announced Wednesday that it had
recovered the bodies of nine Iranian diplomats at the outskirts of
Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani described as "ridiculous" Iran's request from the
Taliban regime to apologize for the diplomats' murder. "The
shooting occurred without the knowledge of the local
commanders. It is highly condemnable that Iranian leaders are
repeating their demand for apology despite our leaders categorical
statement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani rejected any possibility of extraditing the killers of
the Iranian diplomats to Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have our own judicial system and the murderers
will be tried under our own laws in lower and superior courts."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban supreme leader Muhammad Omar has formed a
ten-member commission to probe into the killing. The commission,
he said, has not yet succeeded tracing the killers.
</P>
<P>
In response to Iran's demand for the release of 45 Iranian
nationals detained by the Taliban, he said Iran should first ask
the anti-Taliban alliance to release Taliban's prisoners and then
send its high-level foreign ministry team for talks with militia
officials in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Iran has vowed to avenge the death of its diplomats and has
announced a second major military games on its border with
Afghanistan. The Taliban blamed the death of Iranian diplomats on
renegade Taliban soliders, warning Iran against military action on
Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
