<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Insists on Balanced Palestinian-Israeli Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt Sunday insisted on
reaching a balanced Palestinian-Israeli agreement on further
redeployment as the U.S. savors progress on its attempts to break
the Mideast peace stalemate.
</P>
<P>
"Cairo is seeking to secure balanced agreement between the
Paletinian and Israeli sides in line with the Madrid and Oslo
framework," Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters
following talks between President Hosni Mubarak and U.S. Mideast
peace envoy Dennis Ross in the Mediterranean city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak received a report from Ross, who arrived in Egypt
earlier in the day on a whistle-stop visit, on his negotiations
with Palestinian and Israeli officials in the past four days to
close the gap.
</P>
<P>
Ross said the U.S. efforts being exerted have realized progress
on some topics and that some difficulties still remain regarding a
number of others which need more efforts to be overcome.
</P>
<P>
"But the gap still exists between the two sides," regretted Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Egypt's stance, he reiterated the importance of
achieving balance in any agreement between the Palestinians and
Israelis and preserving the interests of both sides.
</P>
<P>
"No one could possibly imagine that a bad agreement would result
in progress. But all in all, it is an issue up to the Palestinian
leadership to decide," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister categorically denied that Cairo
is applying pressure on the Palestinians not to accept a
watered-down version of the U.S. plan.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered a compromise to the U.S. plan for an Israeli
troop pullback from another 13 percent of the West Bank in
exchange for Palestinian steps on security, saying that 3 percent
should be turned into nature reserves. The Palestinians are yet
to accept it.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is not pressuring the Palestinian Authority to accept
certain ideas. It is definitely not a role we are playing," Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
Ross also denied that his current trip is trying to pressure
Egypt and soften its stance.
</P>
<P>
Ross returned to Jerusalem immediately after his talks in Cairo
to resume negotiations with the Palestinian and Israeli sides.
</P>
<P>
Since his arrival in the region last Wednesday, Ross met with
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat Wednesday
and Saturday, and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Thursday and Friday in a bid to break an 18-month peacemaking
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to make peace with Israel, has
been mediating in the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
