<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Official Calls for Luring Back Capitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The governor of the
Saudi Monetary Fund (Saudi central bank), Hamad Alsayyari, Sunday
called for more incentives to lure back the huge amount of
capitals Saudi Arabians had invested abroad.
</P>
<P>
Alsayyari said that "Saudi citizens have invested huge sums in
the international capital markets and there is a need to attract
these investments back into Saudi Arabia and offer them
incentives to stay in the local markets," according to a report
by the Kuwait News Agency. But he did not gave a figure of
capitals invested abroad by the Saudis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the third seminar on investment products and
services in Saudi Arabia, Alsayyari stressed the importance of
coming up with methods to strengthen and broaden the Saudi
Arabian financial markets and encourage the private sector to
play a greater role.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a need to consider the development of
a more "active and deeper secondary market for government
securities."
</P>
<P>
Alsayyari said that Saudi banks registered big leaps in
their investment programs over the past 10 years, with most
of them offering a wide range of investment products and
services including 100 investment funds with combined assets
reaching 5.8 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
