<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement Between Two Somali Factions May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 13 (Xinhua)-- The Islamic Fundamentalist
Group of Al-Itihad Al-Islam Sunday warned against a possible
collapse of its agreement with the Somali National Front (SNF)
faction signed early last month.
</P>
<P>
Al-Itihad Al-Islam has issued a stern warning to the SNP
faction that the agreement signed in El-Adde Village of Gedo
Region is on tha verge of a total failure unless statesmen,
traditional leaders and elders get up for rescuing the agreement
which has brought about a tangible stability to the region.
</P>
<P>
The strongly worded warning came after Colonel Sheikh Adan
Elmi Jama from the Al-Itihad Al-Islam was shot dead in the Gedo
regional capital of Garbaharrey Town three days ago. Another
official from Al-Itihad was also wounded during the attack.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters via VHF radio here in Mogadishu Sunday,
Hussein Guled Aden, the chief delegate of Al-Itihad Al-Islam for
the implementation of the El-Adde Village Agreement, said four of
his delegation members were also rounded up and taken away to the
border town of Dolow-Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to Aden, the killing of Colonel Jama and the
subsequent arrests made by what he called elements from the SNF
faction has been a deliberate plot set up for undermining the
agreement between Al-Itihad and the main SNF Marehan faction.
</P>
<P>
Aden characterized the new moves as unfortunate and a setback
to the overall agreement which will threaten the security of the
region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Aden who spoke to reporters in Dhamaso Village, 120 km south
of the border town of Bulo Hawo, said his delegation including
the deceased, wounded and the others arrested were in an official
invitation to visit Garbaharrey for the implementation of the
El-Adde Agreement and its modalities. However, he said the rest
of his delegation and himself had fled the town of Garbaharrey
immediately after the killing and the arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
Aden has called the SNF statesmen and elders to be careful of
what is going on and honor the agreement they have signed with
Al-Itihad Al-Islam. He has also called the elders of SNF Marehan
faction to free those arrested soon and give an understandable
explanation to the matter concerned so as to save their agreement
with Al-itihad.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Al-Itihad and the Marehan SNF faction
has brought about the opening of the 180-km road between the
important town of Sulo Hawo and El-Adde Village. The agreement
has also facilitated the free movement of business in the region
even though many other roads still remain closed for landmines
which are yet to be exhumed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian, Turkish FMs Dispute over Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi on Sunday disputed with his Turkish counterpart
Ismail Cem over policies of the two countries, showing sharp
differences between Tehran and Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"I voiced Iran's serious concern on Turkey's military
cooperation with Israel, as other regional countries did,"
Kharrazi said at a joint press conference with Cem who arrived
here on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran and Turkey have different views over
the cooperation with Israel and he has informed Cem of
Iran's stance over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Cem replied that Ankara's cooperation with Tel Aviv is not
against any third country.
</P>
<P>
"I heard some saying against Turkey during the recent
tripartite meeting among Iran, Greece and Armenia" held in
Tehran last week, the Turkish foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi immediately refuted the saying and stated that
foreign ministers of Iran, Greece and Armenia did not talk
about Turkey, but economic cooperation among the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
But the Iranian minister noted that Iran and Turkey have
some common views and stances on regional and international
issues.
</P>
<P>
He said he and Cem discussed in details the issues of
Afghanistan, northern Iraq, Cyprus, border security and
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that the two sides reached the consensus to
hold regular meetings twice a year in order to exchange
views over regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
Both the two foreign ministers agreed that relations between
Tehran and Ankara have been improved during the past six
months and the two countries would make efforts to reduce
their differences.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Turkey exchanged their ambassadors in March to end
a year-long diplomatic row caused by a pro-Islamic speech of
former Iranian ambassador to Ankara Mohammad Reza Baqeri.
</P>
<P>
In February last year, Baqeri was asked to leave Turkey
for insulting the Turkish secular government. In retaliation,
Iran also asked Turkey to recall its ambassador to Tehran
Osman Koruturk.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached agreement to resume their dispatch of
ambassadors in September last year, after the moderate
government of President Mohammad Khatami came to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
