<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Says Israel Wants No Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri Sunday blasted Israeli policy, saying that the Jewish State
does not want peace but to control Arab World, the state-run
National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said in an interview with the Egyptian magazine Rouz
Al-yussef that Israel, which refused to withdraw its troops from
its occupied south Lebanon and Syrian Golan Heights, should be
blamed for the deadlock of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli government has not yet taken a strategical policy
on how to live in the region," he asserted.
</P>
<P>
"In another words, which kind of state does Israel want to be,
to control the Arab countries or live peacefully among them?" he
asked.
</P>
<P>
He said any ideas to control the Arab world will never
succeed. But if Israel wants to choose the latter, it must step
onto the peace road, he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured Syrian Golan Heights in the 1967 Middle
East war and occupied a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between Israel and each of Syria and Lebanon
broke off when the hardline Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu came to power in June, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hariri reiterated that if Israel withdraws from its occupied
south Lebanon and Golan Heights, peace agreement can be signed
within three months.
</P>
<P>
But he said Israel in fact does not want peace and responded by
illogical demands.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Israeli cabinet endorsed the 20-year-old
United Nations Resolution 425 but linked the implementation of
it with the Beirut government security guarantee for its north.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria flatly rejected the offer, asking
the Jewish state to leave the country without any preconditions
as stipulated in the resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
