<HEADLINE> Mandela Urges Sanctions on Angola's UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 13 (Xinhua) -- South African
President Nelson Mandela Sunday urged the implementation of
United Nations Security Council sanctions on Angolan opposition
movement National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Mandela expressed his confidence in the U.N. resolution in
settling the Angolan crisis in his speech on Sunday afternoon at
the opening ceremony of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) summit here in the north of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions on the UNITA include its officials' foreign
trips, in a bid to oblige the former rebel movement to comply
fully with the Lusaka peace protocol signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
On the crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC),
Mandela reiterated Saturday that there should be coordination of
interventions based on the decisions taken at the summits at
Victoria Falls of Zimbabwe and Pretoria of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is critical that all the initiatives being taken should be
harmonized, said the South African president.
</P>
<P>
"We are encouraged by the progress in the Victoria Falls
initiative toward securing peace in the Democratic Republic of
Congo, and in staving off a conflict which threatened to involve
the whole region," attributing the progress made to the quality
of African leadership.
</P>
<P>
According to Mandela who is also the current Chairman of the
SADC summit, the challenge now is to develop and implement the
agreements so that the people of the DRC can determine their own
destiny and embark on reconstruction as a united, democratic,
stable and prosperous nation.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the peace initiatives so far taken by African
leaders will be vital to the inter-dependence and stability of
all the countries in southern Africa and the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also urged SADC member states to work together with
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to "create the mechanisms
which will ensure progress toward processes which will ultimately
result in genuinely democratic elections."
</P>
<P>
The armed clashes in the DRC, the third largest African country,
has drawn nearly half of the 14 SADC members, with Zimbabwe,
Namibia and Angola sending in troops to prop up President Laurent
Kabila's government which is accused by the rebels of corruption
and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Mandela also expressed his concern over
the political situation in Lesotho. However, he added with a
belief that however bitter the debate may be, a solution will be
found.
</P>
<P>
There had been protests in Lesotho against the ruling party
for its alleged rigging in the last elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
