<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Debt Relief for SADC Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 13 (Xinhua) -- South African
President Nelson Mandela Sunday called for debt relief to ensure
the sustainable development for southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
The pace of socio-economic change in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) countries continues to be impeded by
the cost of servicing debt, Mandela said in his speech at the
opening of the SADC summit here in the north of the Indian Ocean
island country.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela, who is also the current Chairman of the
SADC, said he was concerned that in most SADC countries debt
repayments have taken up a "significant proportion" of the gross
domestic products and use up resources which should have been for
funding productive investment, building of houses, education and
the extension of health care.
</P>
<P>
"Our ability to continue lowering inflation and reducing
fiscal deficits is therefore dependent on the willingness of the
creditor countries and institutions to work with us to devise
realistic debt cancellation schedules," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also urged African countries to take advantage of the
opportunities of integration in the global market by initiating a
viable and sustainable regional development plan.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the South African president voiced the determination
of southern African countries to make the region a leading
destination for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"We remain committed to the combination of sound economic
policies, good governance and far-reaching program of
reconstruction and development," pledged the 80-year-old
anti-apartheid hero.
</P>
<P>
The two day summit of the SADC heads of state and government
will also discuss food security, the impact of Asian and Russian
financial crises on the region as well as other issues concerning
regional economic integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
