<HEADLINE> Jordan Cracks down on Underground Opposition Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian security services
have detained 20 members of a banned political party on charge of
membership in illegal organizations, Minister of Information Nasir
Judeh said here Sunday at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The detainees were from the Al Tahrir Party (the liberation
party), which has been officially banned for years, said Judeh.
</P>
<P>
Three of them have been released and the rest will be
transferred to the State Security Court to receive sentences, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The arrests were made after years of investigation, said
Judeh, while refusing to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The Al Tahrir Party is known as the only underground opposition
party that has been officially mentioned by the Jordanian
government so far.
</P>
<P>
This party adheres to Islamic ideology and strives to have the
Islamic law based on the Koran in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Jordan allows the existence of opposition parties, but they
have to be registered and are not allowed to hold underground
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
