<HEADLINE> Libya to Disband Ministry of Arab Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Libya will disband its Ministry
of Arab Unity in the coming few weeks, the Middle East News Agency
(MENA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
MENA quoted informed Libyan sources as saying Sunday that
Secretariat of the General People's Committee for Libyan Unity,
the official Libyan authority assigned with Libyan-Arab affairs
and relations, will be canceled at the upcoming session of the
parliament within weeks.
</P>
<P>
Gomaa Kazzani, secretary of the committee, will attend the Arab
League Council meetings of foreign ministers scheduled in Cairo
Wednesday as his final job. The Arab meeting is expected to
discuss the latest developments in the West-Libya crisis over the
Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the decision was made in line with Libya's
increasing assertion of its African affiliation.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that Libya is taking the step to
protest Arab failure to have the seven-year-old United Nations
sanctions against the Afro-Arab country lifted.
</P>
<P>
In a recent TV interview, Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi rapped
Arab countries for not showing enough support to Libya, while
praising the Organization of African Unity (OAU) for backing its
demand for lifting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed air, arms and diplomatic embargo on the
country in 1992 after Libya failed to hand over two Libyans
suspected of blowing up an American flight over Lockerbie,
Scotland in 1988. The bombing killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The OAU, in its summit meeting in June, adopted a resolution to
defy the sanctions starting from this month if the United States
and Britain fail to make compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
