for the new government by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the NTV Itogi television Primakov said
that he would meet all party factions to discuss the government
formation and submit his proposals to the president by the end of
next week.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the new government must be reorganized by
professionals. Some other Communists could join the Cabinet, but
only if they were professionals, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
The government must do everything to continue the reforms, he
said. "It is necessary to correct some mistakes made in the past".
</P>
<P>
Primakov noted "It should be a socially-oriented economy. We
must remember that even during the transition to a free market, to
an effective economy everything must serve the people."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister emphasized that the government must lean on
the parliament for support, but it cannot be an adjunct of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the newly-appointed Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
and new Chairman of the Central Bank Viktor Gerashchenko, Primakov
said that both men are high-grade professionals, experts. They
were figures chosen right; Gerashchenko is ready to work together
with the government.
</P>
<P>
He also called the appointment of Yuri Maslyukov to the post of
the first deputy Prime Minister absolutely optimal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Primakov declared that he does not aspire to
presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign investments the premier said that the attraction
of foreign investments in Russian industries will be a priority of
the government.
</P>
<P>
"A consistent policy of reforms will be guaranteed", Primakov
said, "We are part of the world economy." 
</P>
