<HEADLINE> Nigerian Head of State Ends Visit to Benin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State
Abdulsalam Abubakar Sunday paid a brief visit to neighboring
Benin and left later in the evening for Lome, Togo.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at Cotonou International
Airport this morning, Abubakar said that he would discuss with
his Beninese counterpart Mathieu Kerekou about bilateral issues
and other problems between the two countries, said a report reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held talks on, among other things, the
situation of two joint ventures set up about 15 years ago along
the border between Nigeria and Benin.
</P>
<P>
Two companies, the Onigbolo Cement Company in southeastern
Benin and the Save Sugar Company in east-central Benin, have gone
bankrupt and were scheduled to be leased out to private
operators.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader noted that Benin always had the best of
relations with Nigeria and President Kerekou was "among the first
leaders sending condolences and advice following the death of
Gen. Sani Abacha" in June.
</P>
<P>
On the process toward civilian rule in Nigeria, Abubalar said,
"Everything is going well and everyone understands the stakes."
The process is "on the right track," he added.  
</P>
