<HEADLINE> Greece to Reduce Taxes for Lower Inflation in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Greece might reduce taxes in
1999 in order to help lower inflation, which was important for the
country to join the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) in
2001, a government official said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Greek Economy and Finance Minister
Yannos Papantoniou said that the government was examing the
possibility of lowering taxes, and if there was room for a
reduction in 1999, this would happen so that inflation might fall
and Greece might easily enter EMU.
</P>
<P>
Greece has lost the chance to join EMU in 1999, but the country
has set January 1, 2001, as the latest entry date into the single
currency.
</P>
<P>
Greece's consumer price inflation reduced from 5.1 percent in
July to 5.0 percent in August. Combined with other criteria, the
inflation rate needs to drop to roughly 2.4 percent before Athens
can join EMU.  
</P>
</TEXT>
