<HEADLINE> Greece Condemns Killing of Albanian Opposition Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday strongly
condemned the killing of a main Albanian opposition leader, saying
those responsible should be arrested and brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
Azem Hajdari, 35, Democratic Party deputy leader, was fatally
wounded and died Saturday in front of Democratic Party
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Another opposition leader, Sali Berisha, blamed Prime Minister
Fatos Nano for the killing and warned him to resign within 24
hours or face "catastrophic consequences", according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Opposition supporters shot and bombed Nano's office and guards
inside after attending Hajdari's funeral in Tirana on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Foreign Ministry spokesman Theodoros Theodorou said
his country was deeply concerned about the political situation in
neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Fearing that the protests and instability would lead to more
serious consequences, Theodorou urged Albania's politicians to
show restraint and prudence.
</P>
<P>
Theodorou said Greece had helped Albania's economic recovery
and growth and participated in international efforts to stabilize
the country, so it was justifiable for Greece to watch closely
over the Greek community living in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said Monday that
Greece was prepared to help any possible influx of refugees from
Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
