<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM Asks to Sign CTBT if Sanctions Lifted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif Monday demanded the Parliament the power to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) if the international economic
sanctions imposed against Pakistan were lifted.
</P>
<P>
A resolution drafted by the government and yet to be placed
before the Parliament purports to "authorize the government to
take a decision on CTBT in the best national interest while fully
safeguarding the nuclear capability of the country and after the
removal of the sanctions and other coercive measures."
</P>
<P>
The two houses of the 304-member Parliament are currently in a
joint session to initiate a rare debate on whether or not to sign
the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
The government of Sharif decided to take the controversial CTBT
issue to the Parliament amid serious economic pressures due to the
sanctions imposed by some western nations after Pakistan's nuclear
tests at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jammat-e-Islami Chief Qazi Hussain Ahmed, addressing
a large public gathering before the Parliament House Monday
evening, demanded the government hold a referendum on whether or
not Pakistan should sign the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution calls upon the international community to
remove sanctions and take urgent steps for a just settlement of
the Jammu and Kashmir dispute between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that passage of the draft resolution is
important before Sharif meets U.S. President Bill Clinton in New
York this month where he is expected to bargain with Clinton for
reviving Pakistan's staggering economy.
</P>
<P>
This could only be possible if the Parliament grants him the
power proposed in the resolution, namely to sign the CTBT if the
economic sanctions are lifted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0029 </DOCNO>
