<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, September 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov on Monday
started his first working day by trying to form a new government
and searching for solutions to the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, whose nomination was overwhelmingly approved at the
State Duma (lower house of parliament) on Friday, called for
tighter discipline and stringent observance of law at a meeting
with senior aides and former Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Primakov, Chernomyrdin said that Acting
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Fyodorov and Acting Finance Minister
Mikhail Zadornov were likely to retain their positions in the new
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chernomyrdin reaffirmed his plan to run in the
presidential elections in 2000. (Russia-Primakov)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross said
Monday that no progress has been made in his effort to finalize
an agreement between Israel and the Palestinians, noting the
disputes centered on security issues.
</P>
<P>
The main problem between the two sides now was Israel's demand
for reciprocity and the lack of Palestinian response to Israel's
security requirements, Israel Radio quoted Ross as telling Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu during a meeting Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Ross is on a renewed mission to bridge the gaps between Israel
and the Palestinians over the long overdue Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He has held separate talks with Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat and Netanyahu since he arrived in the
region last Wednesday. (Israel-Ross-Netanyahu)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Leader of the Afghan Taliban militia Mullah
Muhammad Omar has asked the Taliban forces in central Afghan
province of Bamyan to protect the POWs and ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press of Pakistan quoted Taliban Spokesman Wakil
Ahmad Mutawakil as saying Monday Omar's message has been given to
the Taliban forces in Bamyan, the central Afghan province which
fell into the Taliban's control Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the Taliban-run Radio Shariat warned Iran against a
military assault on its territory.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the Taliban militia and Tehran nose dived
last month following the killing of nine Iranian diplomats by the
Taliban soldiers during their attack on the major northern Afghan
town of Mazar-i-Sharif. (Afghanistan-Omar-POWs) 
</P>
