<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC: Oil Prices Rise Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vienna, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) announced Monday that its basket of
reference crudes rose from 11.99 U.S. dollars per barrel to 12.27
dollars in August.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, because supply in the international oil
market exceeded demand, OPEC's crude prices kept falling. To cope
with the situation, OPEC has cut its daily ceiling production
twice, a total reduction of 2.6 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, OPEC's oil prices remained low. The average price
in August was 11.89 dollars per barrel, compared to last year's
price of 18.68 dollars and OPEC's reference price 21 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Actual daily production has reportedly since dropped and
experts are forecasting a rise in oil prices with the onset of
winter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
