<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Food Program to Provide Foodgrain to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
will provide 355,000 tons of foodgrain for Bangladesh's
flood-stricken people during a penury following the calamity, the
Associated Press of Bangladesh (APB) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The aid package is in addition to the United Nations food
agency's pre-flood allocation of 542,000 tons of foods which are
being utilized for various projects.
</P>
<P>
"We have also proposed to increase the supply of food as the
'need is very high'" due to the over-two-month-long flood that
affected about 30 million people seriously, WFP's country
representative Werner Kiene said while announcing the assistance
at a press briefing Monday.
</P>
<P>
The UN agency does not foresee a famine in the aftermath of
this devastating flood, if all mechanisms work well in the
post-flood program, he said, adding "there is minimum possibility
of food crisis."
</P>
<P>
He mentioned that the U.S. government has announced a food aid
of 400,000 tons while other countries and donor agencies have
pledged around 110,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Bangladeshi government is also importing 200,000
tons of food, apart from the import by private sector, that would
help cope with the present situation, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the WFP representative said they would monitor the
distribution of food at district and township levels through their
teams to make sure that foods are not mis-used. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
