<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Official to Visit U.S. for Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Foreign Secretary
Mostafizur Rahman will leave here Monday night for Washington to
seek more food aid and other relief materials for the millions of
flood victims in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We require an additional 300,000 tons of foodgrains to meet
our needs," Rahman told reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Besides foodgrains, he said he would also require the United
States to provide ready-to-eat food and medicines for the nearly
30 million flood-hit people across the country. The United States
has so far committed 400,000 tons of food grains to flood-stricken
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, the foreign secretary would have
talks with U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State on South Asian
Affairs Karl Inderfurth and other government officials.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said that he would discuss with the U.S. side the
possibility of a 30-percent increase of import of Bangladeshi
garments in the American market and the writing off of Dhaka's
debt of 700 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He would also discuss with U.S. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson about U.S. investment in the South Asian nation's
energy sector in which some American companies have been actively
involved.
</P>
<P>
The over-two-month-long flood has left millions of people
homeless and over 800 dead in Bangladesh, and there are fears of a
possible famine after the flood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
