<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Serie A Likely to Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Teams for Italy's Serie A could
be reduced from 18 to 16 for the sake of top clubs and national
sides, soccer federation chief Luciano Nizzola said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Serie A featured 16 teams from 1934-43 and from 1967-88,
and has hovered between 16 and 18 teams.
</P>
<P>
"I think that in future it would be desirable to return to 16
teams," Nizzola said. "Since it is becoming increasingly
difficult to accommodate the demands of both the clubs and the
various national sides."
</P>
<P>
About 150 foreign players played with Serie A clubs, causing
frequent problems during the qualifying rounds of major
international tournaments such as the World Cup, the European
Championships and the Copa America.
</P>
<P>
Inter and AC Milan are regularly involved in arm-twisting with
Brazilian soccer officials over releasing the likes of Ronaldo
and Leonardo.
</P>
<P>
Clubs also know that the likely emergence of a midweek
European Super League, either under the auspices of UEFA or a
TV-led private consortium, will force them to cut back their
national league commitments.
</P>
<P>
Taking sides with the European Football Union, Nizzola said:
"I think that the Super League should be part of UEFA, which is
an international body. It's hard to think of a championship
managed by private concerns." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Rally Against High Prices in Medan, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of workers and
students Monday held rally in Medan, capital of Indonesia's North
Sumatra province, demanding the lowering of commodity prices,
especially that of automotive spare parts and food.
</P>
<P>
Public transportation in the city was totally paralyzed as
about 6,000 vehicles of the city's public transport fleet lay
idle, Antara News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some of the rallying transport workers threw stones at cars
passing by and at buildings located near the venue of their rally.
They also stopped public buses coming in from outside Medan and
persuaded the newly-arrived drivers to join their demonstration in
front of the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
An estimated group of several hundreds of people stormed and
looted Yuki Simpang Raya Place, one of the city's new and
prestigious shopping centers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate report of any casualty in the attack on
the shopping center but a few shopkeepers needed medical help for
light injuries. Security officers blocked a number of streets
around the shopping center.
</P>
<P>
Until noon Monday, the atmosphere in Medan was still tense, the
agency said, adding that most shops, banks and offices closed
virtually paralyzing all business activities for the rest of the
day.
</P>
<P>
Last week, students in Jakarta, Surabaya, Semarang, Bandung and
other cities held rallies to protest against the spiraling prices
of basic commodities. They urged President B.J. Habibie to take
concrete measures to solve the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few weeks, rice prices have sharply increased to
about 5,000 rupiah (0.45 U.S. dollar) per kilogram, compared to
the Indonesian government's targeted price of 2,000 rupiah per
kilogram. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appropriate Measures by Responsible Gov't, Tung Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong government must
adopt appropriate measures to maintain the integrity and
orderliness of the currency, stock and futures markets to protect
Hong Kong's economy and members of the public from unnecessary
losses, Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is what is expected of a responsible government," Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
To fend off market manipulators, the government decided to
intervene in the stock and futures markets last month, followed by
seven technical measures to strengthen the currency board system
and a 30-point package to tighten market control.
</P>
<P>
"From reports in the local media, the decision and measures
taken by the government have received the support of most Hong
Kong people," the chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
Tung is meeting Legislative Council members and representatives
from political parties in groups Monday and Tuesday to listen to
their views on future policy directions as Tung's second Policy
Address is to be delivered early October.
</P>
<P>
He met with representatives from the Democratic Party, Liberal
Party and the Breakfast Independent Group this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings with party representatives, the chief executive
reaffirmed the government's commitment to maintaining Hong Kong's
status as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
"We have used as reference what is being done in major
financial markets such as those in the U.S., UK and Australia in
drawing up the measures (to strengthen the operation and
monitoring system of Hong Kong financial market)."
</P>
<P>
"We believe these measures will effectively deter market
manipulators from controlling and distorting our markets but will
not affect those investors engaging in normal transactions. In
fact, the interests of these investors will be even better
protected."
</P>
<P>
As for some of the measures that require the enactment of
legislation, relevant bills will be introduced into the
Legislative Council very soon, Tung said, and expressed the hope
that the bills would win the support of the council.
</P>
<P>
Tung said: "When the financial markets are manipulated, the
free market system cannot function normally and investors will
stop coming. This is exactly the unusual situation our markets
have been facing in recent months."
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we must adopt effective measures to quickly restore
order in the free markets to ensure their proper functioning in a
bid to attract investors," Tung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Main Cambodian Parties Agree to Crisis Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 14 (Xinhua) --The three major Cambodian
political parties agreed Monday to meet with King Norodom Sihanouk
in Siem Reap, marking the beginning of a possible resolution to
the political crisis.
</P>
<P>
They reached agreement on three main points:
</P>
<P>
-- not to cause or provoke any public demonstrations;
</P>
<P>
-- to hold a summit in Siem Reap under the chairmanship of the
King and without any pre-conditions;
</P>
<P>
-- the newly elected National Assembly should be convened as
scheduled on September 24.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after Thai Deputy Foreign Minister
Sukhumbhand Paribatra separately met with the leaders of the three
main parties.
</P>
<P>
"I thought the three parties' positions were much closer than
I had realized," Paribatra said after meeting with Chea Sim, the
President of Cambodian People's Party (CPP), Prince Ranariddh,
President of Funcinpec Party, and Sam Rainsy, President of the Sam
Rainsy Party (SRP).
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim was already prepared to participate in the meeting in
Siem Reap, according to the spokesman of his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh said he and Sam Rainsy would meet the king on
September 16 and 17. "We, Sam Rainsy and I, agreed to attend any
summit meeting with the King in Siem Reap," he said.
</P>
<P>
Paribatra began his two-day visit to Cambodia on Sunday. He
met with King Sihanouk in Siem Reap on Sunday and conveyed a
letter from Thai Premier Chuan Leekpai which expressed Thai
concerns over the recent unrest and support for the King in
resolving the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Anti-government demonstrations continued Monday in Phnom Penh,
but on a much smaller scale compared to recent days. Military
police detained at least five protesters and sporadic gunfire
could be heard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
