<HEADLINE> HK Makes Good Progress in Tackling Year 2000 Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Over 99 percent of Hong
Kong government's critical computer and embedded systems would be
year 2000 compliant by the first half next year, a government
paper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a paper tabled at the Legislative Council Information
Technology and Broadcasting Panel meeting, the Information
Technology and Broadcasting Bureau said that as of August 1998,
over 75 percent of the government's critical computer and embedded
 systems had been confirmed to be year 2000 compliant and the
percentage would be raised to 85 percent by the year of the year.
</P>
<P>
For systems which could not achieve compliance by June 30,
1999, the departments concerned had already started drawing up
contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
The paper also revealed that the majority of system
rectification work in the financial services sector was expected
to be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
For instance, about 97 percent of the banking institutions
were expected to achieve year 2000 compliance for their critical
systems by the end of this year and arrangements were being made
for industry-wide test planning and overall contingency planning
for the sector.
</P>
<P>
Good progress was also been achieved in the public utilities
sector, such as electricity and gas companies, telecom providers,
TV and radio broadcasters and other essential services providers.
</P>
<P>
To help remove misconceptions and to minimize unnecessary
anxiety in the community about the impact of the year 2000
problem, the government plans to launch another phase of publicity
program later this year. In addition, a comprehensive survey on
year 2000 compliance would be completed later this year, the paper
revealed.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong government has a web site
(http://www.year2000.gov.hk) on the Internet to update the public
the government's compliance work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
