<HEADLINE> Greece, Finland Agree to Strive for Joint EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Finland agreed here
Monday that the two countries would step up efforts to promote a
joint foreign and security policy by the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with visiting Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said that both
Greece and Finland had suffered the adverse effects of bipolarity
and the experience had made them both more concerned about
regional cooperation and peace.
</P>
<P>
He said that there had been a great deal of emphasis placed on
the economy, but no solutions would be forthcoming if they did not
simultaneously support a joint foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Finland's proposal for a meeting between the EU, the U.S. and
Russia was considered in positive light by Greece, he said, adding
that such a meeting could provide a means to promote this foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
The premier also noted that Athens backed cooperation which
extended beyond the EU to solve problems that were not solely EU
issues.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Ahtisaari, who arrived here Monday for a
four-day official visit to Greece, also met with his Greek
counterpart, Costis Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that the U.N. Security Council should have
the final word on the Kosovo issue and EU partners had to
cooperate to deal with the difficulties facing the group. 
</P>
