<HEADLINE> Foreign Troops Must Withdraw From Congo (K): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior minister of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) reiterated here Monday
afternoon that Rwandan and Ugandan troops should be withdrawn
from his country.
</P>
<P>
V. Mpoyo, a Congolese state minister, told reporters here
outside the International Conference Center where the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) summit meeting is still
going on that there are no rebels or even Tutsis in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
Those now fighting in the east of the country are backed by Rwanda
and Uganda after their several attempts to murder President Laurent
Kabila failed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Once these troops are withdrawn from the central African country,
the situation will return to normal, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the government army are still fighting in
the east of the country and that the SADC alliance, namely the troops
of Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola which are in the country to help prop
up Kabila's 16-month-old government, has not taken part in the
current fighting.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is improving," he added. People in some eastern
part of the country, such as Goma, are now answering the government
call in their efforts to restore peace in the area.
</P>
<P>
Mpoyo also said all members of the SADC are coming to understand
the stand taken by the Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
According to him, there will be a free election next year in his
country, in which any Congolese can participate.
</P>
<P>
The newly appointed Congolese Foreign Minister J.C. Okoto said
during the Non-Aligned Movement meeting early this month in South
Africa that his government is never opposed to democratic polls, but
such election must be held in accordance with the government's plan.
</P>
<P>
Kabila also said earlier that he was committed to hold free and
fair elections by June, 1999, despite what he termed as the aggression
of neighboring Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The conflict would not deter his administration's efforts to rebuild
the DRC into a great nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said only through democratization could the long-twisted
potentials of the vast central African country be dug out.
</P>
<P>
The key to stability in the central African region is Congo's
peaceful transition to democracy, with a broad-based government which
absorbs all political sectors, they urged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
