<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliament Recommends Severing Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) passed a resolution to sever all kinds of relations
with the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) authorized to
dismantle the Iraqi mass destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issed on Monday after an emergency session, the
assembly recommended the severing of relations with the UNSCOM and
halting all its activities in Iraq in case the U.N. Security Council
does not meet the Iraqi demands.
</P>
<P>
Iraq demands that U.N. resolution No. 1194 be annulled to pave
the way for "an open dialogue without threats".
</P>
<P>
The assembly authorized the Iraqi leadership to make
any decisions it deems appropriate to left the U.N.-imposed embargo
on the country in the light of the Iraqi decision on August 5
to suspend cooperation with the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the resolution No. 1194 was contrary to what Iraq
expected of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi assembly concluded by condemning the U.N. Security
Council resolution No. 1194 which put off the discussion on
lefting the embargo pending the retreat of Iraq from its former
decision suspending cooperation with the UNSCOM weapon inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that the resolution No. 1194 was passed
under pressures from the United States and Britain in violation of
Iraq's "territorial integrity and national sovereignty".
</P>
<P>
Iraq threatened in the last few weeks to adopt decisive steps
in case the U.N. Security Council delays the discussion of the
lefting of the embargo indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership, the Revolutionary Command Council and the
country leadership of the ruling Baathist Party, is expected to
meet under President Saddam Hussein later Monday evening or on Tuesday
on the resolution of the National Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
