<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third World to Play Key Role to Save Ozone Layer: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries are s%t
to take central stage in the battle to save the ozone layer,
Klaus Topfer, chief of the Nairobi-based U.N. Environment Program
(UNEP), said in a statement issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The responsibility for saving the ozone layer is now to a
large extent with the developing countries," Topfer said on the
eve of the International Day for the Preservation of the Ozone
Layer, which is to be marked worldwide Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal Protocol, adopted in September 1987, allowed the
third world a grace period to phase out their consumption and
production of ozone depleting substances such as
chloro-fluoro-carbons (CFCs) and halons.
</P>
<P>
"Today, this grace period is almost over. The developing
countries must begin a phase-out of CFCs, halons and carbon
tetrachloride with a freeze starting July 1, 1999," the UNEP
statement noted.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, the share of the developing countries and
Russia (then the Soviet Union) in the total production of CFCs
was 15 percent. In 1996, it was 80 percent. For halons, the share
was 7 percent ten years ago and hits 100 percent currently.
</P>
<P>
In 1986 the consumption of CFCs in the industrializcd
countries was about one million tons and now has been completely
phased out apart from some 15,000 tons for permitted essential
uses only, according to the U.N. data.
</P>
<P>
"The ozone hole will recover but only if they (the developing
countries) implement the control measures next year and complete
their phase-out according to schedule," said Topfer.
</P>
<P>
"The developing country phase-out will be a crucial challenge
for the next 10 years," also said Madhava Sarma, Executive
Secretary of the UNEP Ozone Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Under the Montreal Protocol, the Multilateral Fund has
disbursed about 760 million U.S. Dollars to more than 100
developing states to phase out more than half of their CFC
consumption. The replenishment for the 2000-2002 period will be
negotiated in late 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal Protocol aims to protect the thin layer of ozone
in the stratosphere, located between 10 and 50 kilometers above
the earth, that absorbs all but a small fraction of the harmful
ultraviolet radiation from the sun and protects all life on
earth.
</P>
<P>
Scientific assessments show the abundance of ozone-depleting
chemicals in the lower atmosphere are declining thanks to the
protocol, and that the production of CFCs and halons have
declined by 86 percent in the last ten years.
</P>
<P>
Given full implementation of the protocol by all countries,
the ozone layer will recover by the middle of the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Continue Seeking Agreement with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai said in south Lebanon on Monday that Israel
would continue its efforts to conclude a security agreement with
Lebanon, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The would-be agreement will provide security for Israel's
northern villages and towns, he said during an inspection tour
of Israeli forces in its occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that if such an agreement is reached, the
first thing Israel will do is to withdraw its troops from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 to allegedly protect its north from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the Israeli Cabinet endorsed the
20-year-old United Nations Resolution 425, but linked the
implementation of the resolution with a negotiated security
agreement from the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria firmly rejected the offer, asking
Israel to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon and then
negotiate a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, a strong advocate in Israel for a conditional
withdrawal initiative, said that Israeli forces will continue its
military operations in south Lebanon until an agreement is
reached with Lebanon. 
</P>
