<HEADLINE> Chinese, Irish Prime Ministers Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
and his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern in their talks today agreed
that the first visit ever made by an Irish prime minister to China
since the forging of their diplomatic ties in 1979 will surly push
Sino-Irish friendship and cooperation further ahead.
</P>
<P>
Both sides held a wide-ranging exchange of views regarding
Sino-Irish relations, as well as other international and regional
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to the Irish guests, Zhu expressed
his delight in meeting again with Ahern.
</P>
<P>
Ahern is the first Irish prime minister to visit China in 19
years, Zhu said, voicing his belief that the visit, a major event
in Sino-Irish history, is of great significance in further
promoting the two countries' friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"China attaches great importance to developing its relations
with Ireland," Zhu said, adding that, "though far apart
geographically and having different social systems and cultural
traditions, the two countries have no outstanding disputes or
problems left over by history."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "both countries highly value their own
independence and adhere to foreign policies of peace. They also
share the same or similar views upon quite a number of major
international issues."
</P>
<P>
Over the past 19 years the two countries have made positive
progress in exchanges and cooperation in the fields of politics,
economics, culture and education, hygiene and legislation, Zhu
added.
