<HEADLINE> Mozambique Welcomes Investment by Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government is
ready to welcome Zimbabwean farmers to come and invest in the
agricultural sector in Manica and Tete provinces in the central
and northwestern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Mozambican Minister of Agriculture and
Fisheries Carlos do Rosario recently while he was touring the two
provinces, a Noticias report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will soon dispatch an expert team to the two
provinces to help the departments concerned to accelerate
procedures for absorbing the investment and make a survey and
estimate for the transfer of agricultural facilities, the
newspaper quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mossurize, Sussundenga and Barue counties in Manica Province
and Angonia County in Tete Province are the first four counties
selected to receive farmers from Zimbabwe, South Africa and
Malavi, he said, adding that these counties have fine
agricultural, ecological and climatic conditions for growing such
cash crops as tea, coffee, sun flowers, cotton, tobacco and
citruses, as well as maize, millet, sweet potatoes and other
grain crops.
</P>
<P>
The minister also listed social stability and a series of laws
including land law as guarantees to protect foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Farmers from Zimbabwe and other countries can bring in capital
and technology, while the Mozambican side will provide land and
infrastructures for mutually beneficial cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from simplifying investment procedures, the Mozambican
government has either reduced or exempted import duties for farm
machinery, insecticides and other materials necessary for
developing agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Foreign farmers can also bring in their livestock for breeding
in Mozambique and the import duties have already been reduced,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
They can set up an association of their own and members can
get loans from the bank established by themselves.
</P>
<P>
In line with an agreement between South Africa and Mozambique,
about 25 South African farmers have engaged themselves in
agricultural development in Niassa Province in the north of
Mozambique since last September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
