<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Irish Prime Ministers Hold Talks in Beijing (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu Rongji said Ireland, as member of the European Union (EU),
has made positive efforts to promote Sino-EU relations within the
EU, for which he expressed appreciation.
</P>
<P>
Thanking Ahern for his stance supporting China's entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO), Zhu briefed him on China's
domestic economic situation and recent flood-control efforts.
</P>
<P>
Ahern passed on sympathy and condolences from his government
and people for the Chinese flood victims.
</P>
<P>
He exchanged views on bilateral relations and issues of common
interest with Zhu during April's Second Asia-Europe Meeting in
London, adding that he is convinced that his ongoing China tour
will serve to further the existing friendly ties between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
Ahern noted that four Irish cabinet ministers have visited
China since the new Irish government assumed office, which he said
had laid a sound basis for his current visit.
</P>
<P>
He will strive to enhance Ireland-China ties and continue
efforts to expand exchanges and cooperation between the two
governments and two peoples, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Irish prime minister spoke highly of China's great economic
achievements as a major economy, and its role in the southeast
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said he would continue to encourage Irish business
people to strengthen economic and trade contacts with China and be
far-sighted in a bid to make bilateral economic and trade ties
score even greater progress.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Ireland will make every effort to support
China's entry into the WTO, which he said is in the interests of
both China and the European nations.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Ahern briefed Zhu on the peace process in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said China is glad to see a peace deal has been reached
among the Irish and British governments and the relevant parties
in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
China will positively support this peace process, he said,
adding that it also hopes that all relevant parties continue their
efforts, overcome difficulties and obstacles in the course of
progress and finally realize the permanent peace in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Zhu hosted a welcome ceremony in honor of
his Irish counterpart. After the talks, the two premiers attended
a signing ceremony for an agreement between the two governments on
civil air transport.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, who arrived here earlier today for a five-day official
visit to China as Zhu's guest, is the first Irish prime minister
to visit China since the two countries forged diplomatic relations
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Beijing, Ahern is scheduled to meet with
President Jiang Zemin. And he will also visit Shanghai and the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
