<HEADLINE> Primakov Starts Work in Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov Monday started his first working day by trying to
form a new government and searching for solutions to the country's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, whose nomination was overwhelmingly approved at the
State Duma (lower house of parliament) on Friday, called for
tighter discipline and stringent observance of law at a meeting
with senior aides and former Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
There would "no lobbying, no advantages in business for
organizations, parties or structures" to which they may have been
close in the past, the Itar-Tass news agency quoted Primakov as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The ruble continued to firm up on Monday, trading at 8.5 to
8.7 to the U.S. dollar at the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange
(MICEX), up from Friday's 11.5 to 12 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Primakov, Chernomyrdin said that Acting
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Fyodorov and Acting Finance Minister
Mikhail Zadornov were likely to retain their positions in the new
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"I gave my recommendations on what should be done first of all
in the financial and economic spheres," Primakov said. "In short,
we talked about everything, about all the aspects of the
government's policy."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chernomyrdin reaffirmed his plan to run in the
presidential elections in 2000.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov was also scheduled
to meet with a number of leading economists later Monday to
discuss ways to tackle the economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin will meet with Primakov and other
senior government ministers on Tuesday, Tass cited a source with
the presidential press service as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
