<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Suffers Heavy Flood Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 21 million people
in central China's Hunan Province, about one third of the local
population, were affected by this summer's devastating flooding of
the Yangtze River and Dongting Lake, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that direct industrial and agricultural losses
totalled 32.9 billion yuan (about 3.71 billion US dollars), said
Deng Lei, head of the Disaster Relief Division of the province's
Civil Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of June, severe flooding has ravaged over 100
counties and cities in Hunan, resulting in 629 deaths. The floods
have also inundated 14 county seats, affected 1.32 million ha of
farmland and destroyed 1.23 million houses, Deng said.
</P>
<P>
So far, 180,000 temporary shelters and 3,000 tents have been
set up, and the majority of the flood-affected people have been
properly taken care of, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the provincial government has earmarked 56 million
yuan and 12 million kg of grain for the flood victims, Deng said,
adding that donated funds, clothing and medicine are also being
sent to the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that the authorities are still having
difficulties raising enough funds to rebuild houses, with a fund
shortage estimated at about 500 million yuan. There are still 1.3
million people who do not have sufficient clothes or bedding for
the coming winter, Deng said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, eastern China's Jiangsu Province today
announced that it had lifted the state of emergency along the
part of the Yangtze River that runs through it. The state of
emergency was imposed on July 27 to counter the worst flooding of
the Yangtze River since 1954. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
