<HEADLINE> Kuwait Sends Humanitarian Aid to Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is to send a
batch of humanitarian assistance Monday to the famine-stricken
people in the southern Sudan, Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
Sudan is facing the heaviest flood in almost 50 years, which
has made thousands of Sudanese people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Sudan is deteriorating as the water level
of River Nile is still rising.
</P>
<P>
With the suffering of the Sudanese people, which has been
worsened by the spread of epidemic cholera, "the assistance
became a necessity to save people from starvation and
illness," the Kuwaiti official news agency Kuna said.
</P>
<P>
Although this is the sixth time this year Kuwait has sent
relief supplies to Arab or Islamic countries suffering from
disasters, it is the first time when Sudan receives humanitarian
aid from Kuwait since the Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between Kuwait and Sudan were severed
after Kuwait was freed from the Iraqi occupation, because Sudan
had been one of the several Arab countries that sympathized with
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A sign of thaw of the relations between Kuwait and those it
termed as "hostile nations" emerged during the past couple of
years.
</P>
<P>
Some of the countries, including Sudan, expressed keenness to
resume normal ties with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In July last year, a senior official from the Sudanese Foreign
Ministry paid a visit to Kuwait, the first time in seven years.
</P>
<P>
The official expressed, during his stay, Sudan's support of
Kuwait's territorial sanctity, sovereignty and independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
