<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Habitat Award Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Center for Human
Settlements (Habitat) announced Monday that a Chinese mayor and a
river-protection project in southwestern China have won the 1998
World Habitat Awards together with other five recipients.
</P>
<P>
The awards will be presented on October 5, World Habitat Day,
at a global ceremony in Dubai, United Arab Emirates, said the
Nairobi-based agency in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Mu Suixin, Mayor ob Shenyang, northeastern China, won this
year's Habitat Scroll of Honor Awards because he "has been
instrumental in coordinating and implementing the UNCHS
(Habitat)-supported Sustainable Shenyang Project."
</P>
<P>
"Mayor Mu's political support to this project has created a
receptive environment for new urban management practices, which
are already transforming traditional decision-making mechanisms
by making them more cross-sectoral and more participatory," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Another winner from China is the Fu-Nan River Comprehensive
Revitalization Project in Chengdu, the capital city of Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Rapid economic and industrial development had led to the
deterioration of the physical environment in Chengdu, a city on
the banks of the Fu-Nan River, resulting in problems such as
floods and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
The project, since 1993 when it was started by the Chengdu
Municipal Government, has revitalized an area of four square
kilometers, including 188 roads and streets, 1,291 enterprises
and institutions and 30,000 households along the Fu Nan river.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, 18-kilometer dykes have been built in a bid
to prevent floods and the river has been dredged and widened.
</P>
<P>
The soil along the river has been covered with 23.53 hectares
of greenery to create ecological balance in the city.
</P>
<P>
The other winners are Brazil's Programa de Mobilizacao de
Comunidades, European Forum for Urban Security, Nigerian
Professor Akin L. Mabogunje, Russian scientist Vladimir
Kudryavtsev and Tunisia's Association des Habitants D'el Mourouj
2.
</P>
<P>
All these organizations and individuals are awarded due to
"their outstanding contributions to human settlements
development," said the Habitat.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme for World Habitat Day is "Safer Cities."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Defense Chief Predicts Approval of VFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary
Orlando Mercado Monday predicted that after the protests against
the Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA) are over, the people will
realize that the VFA is "for the national security."
</P>
<P>
He said the government welcomes various groups staging anti-VFA
demonstrations as long as they are peaceful because they are part
of a democratic process.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome these demonstrations. These are just part and
parcel of the debate. Demonstrations are one form of articulating
your views," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Militant groups have staged a series of demonstrations against
the controversial VFA, which if ratified, would pave the way for
military exercises between the Philippines and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of opponents staged demonstrations in front of the
U.S. Embassy in Manila last week. The police were forced to use
tear gas and clashed with the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada has repeatedly made clear that he
supports the ratification of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
"We support the president on that stand. And let the debate
ensue. I think that in the final analysis, the people will realize
that we need the Visiting Forces Agreement for our own national
security," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
The VFA is currently pending in the Senate for approval.
Militant groups have labeled the VFA as part of the move for the
U.S. to re-establish a military base in the country which the
Philippine government strongly denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
