<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Affects Cotton Supply Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- This summer's flooding will
have a slight affect on the nation's cotton supply, according to
an official of the All-China Supply and Marketing Cooperative in
charge of cotton purchase.
</P>
<P>
"The yield is expected to drop somewhat, but China has an ample
supply of cotton in storage," said the woman official, adding that
"the textile industry still continues to face a sluggish market
and the demand for cotton will be met."
</P>
<P>
She predicted that cotton output will reach four million tons,
down close to 500,000 tons on last year's output.
</P>
<P>
She admitted that the floods in the Yangtze River since June
adversely affected the growth cycle in major cotton producing
areas, such as Hunan, Jiangxi and Hubei provinces.
</P>
<P>
"However, cotton is growing well in other areas in the Yangtze
River and Huanghe River valleys and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region," according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the middle of August show that floods
affected 530,000 ha. of cotton, including the total destruction of
crops on 130,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the State Development Planning Commission
lowered the purchase price in April, planting cotton continues to
be profitable than growing other crops. Cotton has been planted on
4.3 million ha for 1998, with the acreage basically equalling last
year's level.
</P>
<P>
She noted that low temperatures and abnormal precipitation in
the early and middle parts of the growth cycle will extend the
normal maturation period by as much as two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
