<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Boosts Presense in ITU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China is boosting its role as
a standard setter in the global telecommunications market by
enlarging its presense in the International Telecommunications
Union (ITU).
</P>
<P>
At a Study Group 7 meeting of the ITU standardization
department which opened here today, China put forward six
suggestions for consideration at the 14-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
This is the first high-level meeting of the influential
international body to be held in China.
</P>
<P>
Wen Ku, a Ministry of Information Industry (MII) official who
presided at the meeting, said this marked China's change from a
passive follower into a standard setter in the field of data
network and open system communications.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu Junhua, head of the Chinese delegation, the six
suggestions they made include adding a Chinese language function
to data communications networks, and running Internet protocol
(IP) over fiber optical networks.
</P>
<P>
She said these innovative technologies have been uniquely
developed by China and, if accepted by ITU as universal standards,
will open up a huge market for China's technology and equipment,
and enhance the competitiveness of the country's
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 120 million telephone lines and boasts
the second-largest telecommunications network in the world,
expected to become the world's largest by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Herb Bertine, chairman of the Study Group 7 of the ITU, said
China has been increasing its presense in ITU standardization
department activities.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that with 188 members around the world, the ITU wields
great power in influencing the adoption of technical and service
standards in the world's telecommunications market. She said that
no one can afford to loose markets by ignoring the standardization
suggestions of the ITU.
</P>
<P>
China has set forth its own candidate for director of the ITU
standardization department, to be decided by election at a ITU
meeting later this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
