<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Issues Balk Progress in Talks: Ross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross said Monday that no progress has been made in
his effort to finalize an agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians, noting the disputes centered on security issues.
</P>
<P>
The main problem between the two sides now was Israel's demand
for reciprocity and the lack of Palestinian response to Israel's
security requirements, Israel Radio quoted Ross as telling Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu during a meeting Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Ross is on a renewed mission to bridge the gaps between Israel
and the Palestinians over the long overdue Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He has held separate talks with Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat and Netanyahu since he arrived in the
region last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The envoy traveled to Egypt Sunday to update President Hosni
Mubarak on his talks with the Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
Egypt plays a mediating role in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross has succeeded in resuming meetings of several committees
from Israel and the Palestinians working on interim issues such
as the airport and seaport in Gaza, and safe passage between Gaza
and the West Bank. The committees broke off their work four months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet secretary Danny Naveh and senior Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat, heads of the steering committees, met
Sunday night at U.S. Ambassador Edward Walker's house and
discussed these secondary issues.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai expressed optimism
Monday over the Israeli-Palestinian talks. He was quoted by
Israel Radio as saying that if the Palestinians showed
flexibility by coordinating Israeli demands with the American
initiative, then it would be possible to sign an agreement soon.
</P>
<P>
The American initiative calls on Israel to pullback troops from
a further 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for
Palestinian measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But Israel is demanding that 3 percent to be handed over to the
Palestinians be designated as a nature reserve, where Israel
would retain full security control. The Palestinians rejected the
idea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
