<HEADLINE> S.Korea Likely to Buy Missile Defense System in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea is considering
buying a U.S.-made Patriot or Russian S-300 missile defense system
in the year 2000, Defense Minister Chun Yong-taek said Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea suspended the plan to purchase a missile defense
system last year because of the high cost, the minister said at a
press conference 15 days after the Democratic Peoples Republic of
Korea (DPRK) launched a rocket to place a satellite into orbit.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Russian and U.S. officials reportedly lobbied
fiercely to sell their defense systems to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
A report said that the U.S.-made Patriot system costs more than
one billion U.S. dollars, but the Russian one is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
However, some South Korean military officers are skeptical
about the effectiveness of any air-defense system because of the
proximity of Seoul and key military bases to the DPRK border, it
said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. forces in South Korea have reportedly deployed a Patriot
battalion to protect its key bases there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
