<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Says Clinton's Visit Likely to Be Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister's
Principle Secretary Brajesh Mishra said Monday that U.S. President
Bill Clinton's planned visit to India in November this year is
likely to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
This is the first open announcement by a senior Indian official
of possible postponement of Clinton's visit to India. Since India
conducted nuclear tests in May this year, the U.S. side has kept
saying that the president's visit to South Asian countries was
under review.
</P>
<P>
Clinton planned to visit Pakistan, India and Bangladesh in
November this year in a bid to enhance mutual understanding and
cooperation between America and the three nations, yet the nuclear
tests by India and Pakistan have made the visit uncertain.
</P>
<P>
Together with other countries, the United States not only
condemned the nuclear tests by the two countries, but also imposed
economic sanctions on them. In its four rounds of talks with the
two countries, the United States strongly urged them to stop
further nuclear tests and sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT) with no conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the United States has linked progress of
the talks with the visit.
</P>
<P>
Mishra said that India is willing to go forward towards signing
the CTBT provided the question of its linkage to disarmament is
worked out. He made it clear that India is not very close to
signing CTBT. He said that negotiations were going on with the
United States and some other countries.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the government's planned talks with political
parties on the CTBT, Mishra said that meetings would begin this
week to seek consensus on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
