<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton's advisers flooded the Sunday talk
shows in an effort to blunt the momentum building in Congress
for a formal impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov pledged to turn Russia
toward a "socially oriented economy," distancing himself form the
capitalist-oriented policies engendered by governments here
since the collapse of the Soviet system seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States began in earnest the wrenching debate
that could determine the future of Bill Clinton's presidency. In
interviews around the country, people expressed revulsion at the
president's behavior but reluctance to put the nation through
the trauma of a presidential resignation or impeachment.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The IMF pledged to support Brazil if the country needs
funds to defend its currency. Brazil's stock market surged 13
percent, but the regional giant remains under pressure from
investors.
</P>
<P>
-- Northwest pilots approved a new four-year contract. But
the strike's effects are likely to linger, as Northwest said it
expects to post losses in the third and fourth quarters and for
all of 1998. The airline began recalling workers who had been
temporarily laid off and announced a plan to return to its full
schedule by Sept. 21. 
</P>
