<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rouble Devaluation Affects Border Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The massive devaluation of the
Russian rouble since mid-August has affected the tourism industry
on the Sino-Russian border, according to official sources in this
capital of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
"Both the number of Russian tourists entering China and the
number of vehicles going through the Manzhouli checkpoint have dived
some 30 percent since August 17," a Chinese border official told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The rouble was traded at 6.6 to the US dollar on August 17, but
its exchange rate plunged to 21.2 to the US currency in the following
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The past regular scenes of long lines of vehicles waiting to
enter and exit China are rarely seen now, the official said.
</P>
<P>
At a border market on the Chinese side, pedlars had little to
do, as business was extremely slow.
</P>
<P>
"I have sold nothing in the past two days," a woman shopkeeper
said. "Without the Russians, we are almost out of business," she
added.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show that the number of Russian
pedlars travelling to China has fallen by 90 percent since August
17. Moreover, the purchasing power of those who do come has
dropped significantly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
