<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aids Threatens S. African Labor Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South African workforce is
being threatened by fastest growing Aids epidemic in the world, local
daily Business Day reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1,500 new HIV infections in South Africa every day.
By the year of 2000, more than 20 percent of workforce in the country
will be HIV positive, according to a report released at a Partnerships
Against Aids Conference held in Pretoria at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attracting political, business, medical and labor
leaders, was aimed at alerting participants to the seriousness of the
Aids problem in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Welfare Minister Geraldine Fraser Moleketi was quoted as saying
that about 4.5 million adults would be HIV positive by 2005. By the
end of 1997, it was estimated that three million people had been
infected.
</P>
<P>
Moleketi said South Africa had about 200,000 orphans who had lost
their parents to Aids and this figure could go up to one million in a
few years.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma, who participated in the conference,
also said that with such a high number of young, economically active
people being HIV infected, South African market base would shrink.
</P>
<P>
She said it was important for business to get involved to promote
Aids awareness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
