<HEADLINE> Mullah Omar Asks Taliban to Protect POWs in Bamyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Afghan
Taliban militia Mullah Muhammad Omar has asked the Taliban forces
in central Afghan province of Bamyan to protect the POWs and
common people.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press of Pakistan quoted Taliban Spokesman Wakil
Ahmad Mutawakil as saying Monday Omar's message has been given to
the Taliban forces in Bamyan.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Taliban forces have been asked to
treat the POWs and common people in Bamyan, the central Afghan
province which fell into the Taliban's control Sunday, in a good
manner and protect their lives.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban are reported to have entered Bamyan city and the
opposition forces have fled from the area without any resistance,
leaving behind their arms and military hardware.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to another report from the Afghan capital
of Kabul, the Taliban militia continued its advance through the
opposition-controlled territory Monday, while reinforcing its
western borders with Iran where 200,000 Iranian soldiers are to
conduct a massive military exercise.
</P>
<P>
There were also reports of as many as 10,000 fresh Taliban
soldiers being sent to western Afghan province of Herat which
borders Iran.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the Taliban-run Radio Shariat warned Iran against a
military assault on its territory, saying that "we have enough
solders to resist any attack."
</P>
<P>
Relations between the Taliban militia and Tehran nose dived
last month following the killing of nine Iranian diplomats by the
Taliban soldiers during their attack on the major northern Afghan
town of Mazar-i-Sharif.  
</P>
</TEXT>
