<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets U.N. Human Rights High Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During a meeting with Robinson here today, Qian said this year
marks the 50th anniversary of the world declaration on human
rights. Over the past 50 years, with unremitting efforts, the
international community has scored many achievements in the field
of human rights including the collapse of centuries-old
colonialism, and apartheid in South Africa, Qian said, adding that
the rights of women, children and other social groups have also
drawn the common attention of the international community.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has played an important role in this
progress, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a peaceful international environment is the
first prerequisite for enhancing and protecting human rights, and
all nations should foster and promote friendly ties with each
other and settle their differences through equal dialogues on the
basis of the U.N. Charter and the Five-Principles of Peaceful
Co-Existence.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government attaches importance to
cooperation with the United Nations in the area of human rights
and has joined 17 international covenants on human rights. China
signed the international covenant on economic, social and cultural
rights last October, and will sign the international covenant on
civil and political rights next month, Qian told Robinson.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates the fact that Robinson has proposed dialogue
and cooperation and advocates that all human rights should be
equally underlined ever since she became the U.N. high
commissioner for human rights, Qian noted.
</P>
<P>
Robinson said that China has played an important role in
safeguarding world peace and security as a permanent member of the
U.N. Security Council. China supports the purpose and principles
of the U.N. Charter, and has actively participated in
international affairs including human rights, acceding to many
international covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
She said she was quite impressed by the great progress made
by the Chinese government in promoting and protecting human rights.
</P>
<P>
Robinson arrived in China on September 6 at the invitation of
the Chinese government. During her stay she has held talks with
the leaders of China's Foreign Ministry, the Supreme People's
Court, the Justice Ministry and other departments.
</P>
<P>
She also toured Shanghai and Tibet, as well as Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
