<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judiciary Shake-up Successful (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) - In an unprecedented internal
shake-up of the judiciary, China reshuffled a considerable number
of courts and prosecutorial offices and disciplined nearly 5,000
judges and prosecutors in the first eight months this year.
</P>
<P>
Courts had also corrected 8,110 misjudged cases by August and
prosecutors reconsidered 1,125 mishandled criminal offenses by
July.
</P>
<P>
President of the Supreme People's Court Xiao Yang and
Procurator-General of the Supreme People's Procuratorate Han
Zhubin revealed these figures today when reporting to the Civil
and Judiciary Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC) on
their work in the "Intensified Educational Rectification Movement."
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the top legislature, the NPC Standing Committee, Li
Peng, and vice-chairman Cao Zhi attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The rectification movement was begun during the central
government's new term in March in response to criticism by
NPC members.
</P>
<P>
As part of this movement, the general public, including NPC
deputies, were invited to air their dissatisfaction with judges
and prosecutors and comment on their work. Courts and
procuratorates were asked to focus on their own illegal practices,
especially those long-pending cases which have drawn public
complaints. The internal check and balance system was also
strengthened to consolidate the results of this campaign.
</P>
<P>
In terms of leadership, 177 courts at provincial, prefectural
and county levels have been reshuffled and unqualified leaders
removed; 326 prefectural level and 1,827 county level
prosecutorial offices have been scrutinized by the Party's
organizational departments and higher offices, which also led to
rectification of prosecutorial offices with weak or corrupt
leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planning Official Recommends Moderately Fast Growth for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China needs to pursue
moderately fast growth of seven to eight percent for the remaining
years up to the end of this century, after having maintained a
growth momentum of ten percent for the past 20 years, according to
a planning official here today.
</P>
<P>
"It is inappropriate for the Chinese economy to keep a high
growth of 10 percent for the coming years, given the new changes
occurring in the economic system, and in supply and demand, as
well as the global economy," Bai Hejin, secretary general of the
State Development Planning Commission (SDPC), told an ongoing
forum.
</P>
<P>
Bai said any economic growth target needs to be based on the
potential of an economy, and that China's economy will be aiming
at a growth of seven percent for the first ten years in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the accelerated growth in investment, consumption
and production from the second half of this year, Bai said it is
possible for the national economy to grow by eight percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the growth is a bit lower than eight percent, it will
still be one of the fastest growths in the world," Bai added.
</P>
<P>
Also a spokesman for the SDPC, Bai predicted that China's
economy will pursue growth of seven to eight percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"If the national economic growth can stay near eight percent in
1998, a growth of 6.8 percent for the next two years will be
enough for the Chinese economy to reach the growth target of eight
percent for the Ninth Five Year Plan period (1996-2000)," said Bai.
</P>
<P>
Bai also noted that the growth target of eight percent this
year has actually been set as a psychological lever, in view of
the past high growth mode, the increasing unemployment pressure
due to economic restructuring and the wavering confidence of
overseas investors in the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
"Rapid growth is not the only thing we want to pursue, and
economic growth should never be obtained at the cost of the
quality of the economy, " warned Bai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hang Seng China Enterprises Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Hang Seng China Enterprises
Index gained 16.51 points to close at 336.32 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Index, introduced in August 1995, tracks the overall
performance of 40 China's state-owned enterprises listed on the
Hong Kong Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng MidCap 50 Index increased 10.98 points from the
previous session to close at 624.07.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng MidCap 50 Index comprises 50 stocks ranked from 101
to 150 on the Hong Kong bourse in terms of market capitalization
and turnover.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index soared 37.39
points to close at 761.44.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index tracks the
performance of 43 locally-listed companies with a significant
equity interest held by entities in China.
</P>
<P>
The three segmented Hang Seng indices are devised by Hang Seng
Index (HSI) Services Limited, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hang
Seng Bank. 
</P>
