<HEADLINE> Peace Talks With NDF Still Open: Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Palace maintained that peace talks with the National Democratic
Front (NDF) rebels remain open, but under two non-negotiable
conditions, Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the fate of the talks are in the hands of NDF
Chief Political Consultant Jose Maria Sison and NDF Chief
Negotiator Luis Jalandoni who, he stressed, have to be "more
reasonable with their demands for the sake of lasting peace and
development in the country."
</P>
<P>
Barican said the government is ready to resume talks with the
NDF provided that the negotiation is pursued within the framework
of the Philippine Constitution and that the implementation of the
agreement on human rights and international humanitarian law
should apply to both parties.
</P>
<P>
"The ball now is in the court of the NDF...The communication
lines remain open, including back channels of communications to
resolve the impasse," Barican added.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora was hopeful
that the two panels would return to the negotiating table but
under clearly defined status -- as the Philippine government and a
rebel group talking peace.
</P>
<P>
"We could not proceed under the premise that there are two
governments in the country. Once they recognize that they are
talking to the government of the Philippines, we will be back
within a day," he said.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of the President, the government panel
suspended peace talks with the NDF after the rebel group made
"misleading" statements that the two panels have agreed to conduct
the peace talks outside of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The NDF is one of the major rebel groups operating in the
southern Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
