<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher on Bargain in Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) --Bargain hunters encouraged by
Friday's rise on Wall Street pushed the local sharemarket higher
Monday, albeit on low volume.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 41.9 points higher at 2,510.2,
with blue chip shares receiving most of the buying attention.
</P>
<P>
"We had a sizable sell off on Friday. There was pretty much
bargain hunting coming in today," Hartley Poynton equities dealer
Ned Shamay said.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the institutional investors are sidelined and waiting
for some direction," Shamay said, identifying a forthcoming speech
by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan this week as an
event the market was awaiting.
</P>
<P>
The Australian market was also encouraged by a 310 point rise,
to 14,227, on the Nikkei index on speculation the Japanese
government was about to implement banking reforms.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index rose 67.6 points to 4,407.9.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares slightly underperformed the market, with the
Australian Labor Party suggesting it would block mergers among the
key banks if voted in at the forthcoming federal election.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was up 21.8 cents, Commonwealth was
20.7 cents higher, ANZ was up 13 cents, while Westpac added seven
cents.
</P>
<P>
Insurance major AMP finished 35 cents stronger, Telco company
Telstra was up 9.8 cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index added 22.2 points to 979.7, with BHP
jumping 35.1 cents, while Rio Tinto rose 42.6 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector was 31 points stronger at 1,046.0 with the
bullion price down 3.10 per ounce at 290.65 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 243.05 million shares traded at a value of 701.69
million Australian dollars (413.99 million U.S. dollars), with 538
rises, 407 falls and 355 steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
