<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Silicon Valley Forge Technology Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and Silicon
Valley have forged business and technology ties in face of the
challenges of the knowledge-based 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Industrial Technology Center (Tech Center) and
the Economic Development Alliance for Business (EDAB) of East Bay
Region in Silicon Valley signed a joint partnership agreement here
Monday, promising to promote exchange of technology, information
and expertise between academia, research institutes and
enterprises in the two places.
</P>
<P>
Silicon Valley, the home to 7,000 technology-based companies,
is the very epitome of innovation and cutting-edge technology,
leading the world in issuing patents, attracting venture capital
and creating new products.
</P>
<P>
Lee Grissom, secretary of California Trade and Commerce Agency,
spoke at Monday's signing ceremony: "It (the agreement) is a
statement of trust between California and Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"We are both in the Pacific Rim and facing the challenges of
the information age. Our future is intertwined, and we shall share
technology and skill and work together to ensure a prosperous
future," said the secretary.
</P>
<P>
Dr James Liu, chief executive officer of Hong Kong's Tech
Center, said on the same occasion: "The new alliance with the EDAB
can bring technology, knowledge, support and business
opportunities from Silicon Valley to Hong Kong and back again."
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two organizations will link up
respective Internet databases, support technology matchmaking, and
foster global business expansion.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, they will join hands to facilitate business
collaboration and technology application between the two regions
in such key areas as telecommunications, environmental,
electronic, biotechnology, software and multimedia industries.
</P>
<P>
It is the third partnership document Hong Kong has signed with
other technology and innovation hubs; the first two were inked
with Guangzhou and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1993, the Tech Center is a statutory body charged
with the mission to promote application of new technology in Hong
Kong industry, while EDAB plays a similar role in the East Bay
Region in Silicon Valley.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Presidential System in Israel: Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu on Monday ruled out the possibility of
introducing the presidential system in Israel.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by Netanyahu's office said that even it is
a good idea, there is no point of discussing the initiative which
has absolutely no chance of being approved by the Knesset
(parliament).
</P>
<P>
The idea was suggested by Avigdor Liberman, former director
general of Netanyahu's office. The proposed new system will give
the prime minister the authority similar to that of president of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Liberman said that the new system will enable the prime
minister to concentrate on matters of the state and be relieved of
dealing with coalition issues.
</P>
<P>
Should such a system be introduced, he noted, there will be no
need for Israel to have a president.
</P>
<P>
Liberman, s member of ruling Likud party, said that the
central committee of his party will discuss the idea.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Rafel Eitan, leader of Tzomet
party, severely criticized the proposal, which he called was "part
of a political plan to take over the power of the country and turn
it into a totalitarian regime."
</P>
<P>
So far all Israeli governments have been based on coalition of
several parties, since no party has ever received enough Knesset
seats to form a government by itself.
</P>
<P>
And the prime minister has to balance the interests in the
coalition before he makes a resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
