<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets UN Human Rights High Commissioner (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
met with Mary Robinson, United Nations high commissioner for human
rights, here today. They had a friendly talk on international
cooperation for promoting, advancing and safeguarding human rights.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China is a developing country with a population of
1.2 billion. "To develop and protect human rights, we should first
take into account our national conditions. That is to place
economic growth in priority in order to feed and clothe the
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, China places democratic and legal
development in an important position in the process of economic
growth, and the advancement of civil and political rights for
the people through judiciary and executive measures.
</P>
<P>
"China will further expand socialist democracy, improve the
socialist legal system, rule the country according to law,
build up a socialist nation of the rule of law, ensure that the
people enjoy extensive rights and liberty, and respect and
safeguard human rights," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Robinson told Jiang that as the first UN human rights high
commissioner to visit China, she was delighted to tour Beijing,
Tibet and Shanghai, and that she considers her visit "helpful and
valuable."
</P>
<P>
During her journey she witnessed the socio-economic progress
made by China over recent years. "China has scored a tremendous
accomplishment in promoting and protecting the economic, social
and cultural rights of its people," she said. She was also deeply
impressed by the efforts made by China to strengthen legal
construction and carry out legal reform.
</P>
<P>
China, a permanent member of the UN Security Council, is a
responsible country, she noted, adding that her office is willing
to strengthen human rights cooperation with China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
