<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Overshadowed by Yen Movement to  End Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
a little weaker Monday after trading quietly in a well-trod range,
largely over-shadowed by movements in the U.S. dollar against the
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended here at 59.72 U.S. cents from 59.92
late Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bell Commodities foreign exchange specialist Markus Helsing
said the U.S. dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate had been all over
the place and had traded through a range of almost two yen.
</P>
<P>
In its September bulletin, released Monday, the Reserve Bank of
Australia (RBA) said it spent 310 million Australian dollars (186
million U.S. dollars) in net spot foreign exchange transactions in
August.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar tumbled to 55.30 U.S. cents in late
August and the U.S. Federal Reserve stepped into the market on
behalf of the RBA.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics' wage cost index for the
second quarter will be released on Thursday and market consensus
is an 0.8 percent increase with forecasts ranging between 0.6 to
0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
International market participants were also keenly awaiting a
speech by U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan at the
House Banking Committee public hearing on the global economic
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan is expected to outline the position of the U.S.
economy in the global economic crisis and perhaps give some
indication on whether he will cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 78.89 Japanese yen from 78.95
and 1.0178 German marks from 1.0091. 
</P>
