<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Taliban Leaders' International Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's special envoy on
Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi on Monday called for a trial of
leaders of the Afghan Taliban militia by an international court
for "racial and religious cleansing in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Boroujerdi made
the call in a speech at Tehran University and said that the
Taliban's killing of Iranian diplomats and reporter would not be
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban on Thursday admitted the death of nine Iranian
diplomats by its renegade troops in Mazar-e-Sharif in northern
Afghanistan on August 8 when the group took over the city. Iran
later said that an IRNA reporter was also killed by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said a technical team of the International Committee of
the Red Cross accompanied by an Iranian technical team was
dispatched to Afghanistan before Monday noon to transfer the
bodies of the killed back to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Popular demand for revenge has been mounting in Iran.
Boroujerdi said that it would not be difficult for Iran to conquer
Afghanistan, but the policy of the Iranian government was based on
non-interference and restoration of permanent peace in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban obtained the victories with direct
interference of Pakistan. However, he said, the Afghan people
would not tolerate such an intervention, and historical experience
showed that the Afghan people would not remain silence towards
foreign presence in their country.
</P>
<P>
Iran has reportedly been supporting the opposition forces,
which now seemed unable to resist the preponderance of the student
militia, who already controlled over 90 percent of the country and
imposed a strict version of Islamic rule there.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that Iran recalled 70 percent of its diplomats
three days before the fall of Mazar-e-Sharif, the opposition's
stronghold in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian foreign ministry discussed the situation in Afghanistan
and decided to keep 30 percent of its diplomatic mission in the
city according to previous experience, he explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
