<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Bonds in Short Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Investors' demand for
government bonds outstrips supply by more than 150 billion baht
(375 million U.S. dollars) in Thailand, the Thai Bond Dealing
Center said.
</P>
<P>
For institutional investors such as mutual funds and insurance
firms, government bonds offer higher returns with lower risks than
equities, property and corporate debt, the center said in a
statement available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Development of the bond market has been hampered by thin
liquidity and the lack of a benchmark for pricing new issues. As
well, years of fiscal surpluses meant that few government bonds
were issued.
</P>
<P>
The few issues available were purchased mainly by local
financial institutions and held to fulfill reserve requirements,
resulting in little trading.
</P>
<P>
But Thailand's economic crisis has forced the government to
issue more bonds to raise capital to offset declining tax revenues
and the cost of financial reform.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the government approved the issue of 500
billion baht (42.5 billion U.S. dollars) worth of domestic bonds
to refinance the liabilities of the Financial Institutions
Development Fund (FIDF).
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand has already auctioned more than 125
billion bath (312 million dollars) worth of one-year bonds since
June 22.
</P>
<P>
To help establish a benchmark and yield curve for the market,
the central bank last week began auctioning longer-maturity
government bonds. Last Friday, it issued 10.39 billion baht (250
million dollars) worth of two-, three- and five-year bonds.
</P>
<P>
Investors' demand has grown steadily over the past several
months. The first sale of one-year bonds in June had an accepted
yield of 12.75 percent, versus 11.9 percent in the latest sale.
Lower yields mean higher prices at auction, indicating high
investors' demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Offer One-Stop Service for Top Taxpayers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Revenue Department of
Thailand is to give comprehensive services to 500 companies which
are the top taxpayers of the department, a statement of the
department available Monday said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the department plans to establish a
special office to give comprehensive services to the 500 top
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
The companies account for 80 percent of the department's tax
take, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
For fiscal 1998, which ends this month, the department expects
tax collections to reach 488 billion baht (12.2 billion U.S.
dollars), while next fiscal year's target has been set at 530
billion baht (13.25 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
To increase efficiency in tax collection, the department
intends to make the office a one-stop service for these companies.
</P>
<P>
Apart from smoothing the payment process, the office will
advise on tax problems and provide tax-related information ranging
from changes in laws to announcements on tax matters.
</P>
<P>
The department hopes the establishment of the special office
will increase the government's tax haul and that taxpayers will
become more willing to pay as procedures become much more
convenient.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that an expert has been assigned by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to work closely with the
department for one year to establish the office and help the
department streamline its operation.
</P>
<P>
Increasing tax collection efficiency has been included in
Thailand's latest commitments to the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
