<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: South Korea Trying to Stimulate Ailing Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea announced an
economic stimulus package last week after its economy plunged into
a deeper recession featured by sharp contraction of the gross
domestic product and domestic consumption in the past months.
</P>
<P>
The package, which highlights a boost in domestic demand,
includes measures to expand the money supply, increase credit
guarantees for small and medium enterprises, exporters and housing
builders, and enlarge consumer financing instruments for durable
goods such as houses.
</P>
<P>
The measures came when indicators for industrial activity
showed unprecedented bad results and businesses were complaining
that unless prompt measures were taken immediately, the ailing
economy would slip into an irreversible slump.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the central Bank of Korea registered a 6.6 percent
decline in GDP in the second quarter of this year, the worst
performance in the past 18 years, which came after a 3.9 percent
contraction in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The nation's economy showed a negative growth for seven months
in a row since January while output fell to minus 10.8 percent
from a 3 percent last December.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted deeper contractions of the gross domestic
product and domestic consumption because of wage cuts and mass
layoffs in the coming months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The package is described as the best option the government has
to take to keep the country's hard-earned economic foundation from
collapsing due to measures imposed by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) last December. The country signed an agreement with the
monetary body at that time for a bailout loan of 58 billion
U.S. dollars after suffering a financial crisis triggered by
corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The government said it had originally planned to put forward
the stimulus package in October this year as soon as the current
economic restructuring almost ends.
</P>
<P>
Under a government-proposed restructuring scheme, 55 nonviable
companies were forced out and five troubled commercial banks were
shut down in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, extensive institutional reforms were implemented.
The regulatory framework on financial institutions was reinforced
while measures to enhance corporate transparency were taken.
</P>
<P>
The government's stimulus plan is believed to be designed to
ease the credit crunch, in which more than 17,000 enterprises
collapsed after the IMF-imposed austerity measures were put into
force.
</P>
<P>
However, officials said if the central bank expands the money
supply sharply, credit woes could be relieved to a certain extent
even though the ailing financial system has yet to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the government has failed to take substantial
measures to relieve debt-laden companies while government
officials say it would be impossible to trim their debt-to-equity
ratios below 200 percent by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the corporate debt problem still remains unresolved
even though the country's five largest conglomerates -- Hyundai,
Daewoo, Samsung, Lg and SK -- have agreed to mergers of their
subsidiaries. It will take time to see satisfactory results of the
mergers.
</P>
<P>
Observers warned that current economic situation may be
similar to what was seen last November when the financial crisis
hit the country, so South Korea has no reason and time to be
complacent over its increasing foreign exchange after its usable
foreign exchange reserves hit 44 billion dollars last Month.
</P>
<P>
Some said that Russia's financial turmoil and the yen's
weakness will continue to pose latent threats to the country's
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Hit Areas Witness Rapid Industrial Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The industrial sector of the
flood-stricken provinces in the Yangtze River Valley witnessed an
upsurge this August, according to statistics from the State
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
In August, the growth rate for industry in east China's Jiangxi
and Anhui provinces increased by 6.2 and 3 percentage points over
July, while those in central China's Hubei and Hunan provinces
rose 4.6 and 1.2 percentage points respectively.
</P>
<P>
The commission attributed the rise of industrial growth rates
to a new demand for medicines, food products and construction
materials which appeared in conjunction with the flood-fighting
activities and home rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
In Hunan Province, for example, the output of Chinese medicines
increased by 33 percent, and steel products by 23 percent last
month, helping to drive local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The floods affected production less in August, as the water
levels were receding by then, which also helped the local
industrial sector grow faster, noted the commission.
</P>
<P>
These provinces kept pace with industrial production in those
areas which were spared any flooding.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the State Statistics Bureau show that in
August, China's industrial incremental output increased by 7.9
percent over the same period last year, and 0.3 percentage points
higher than in July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
