<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Massive Gas-Development Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to step up gas
development this year in order to double its gas production
capacity to 30 billion cubic meters by the year 2005 as part of a
major energy-resources development strategy.
</P>
<P>
According to experts with the China National Petroleum Corp
(CNPC), China is expected to verify additional onshore gas
reserves of one trillion cubic meters by the end of the century,
with a cumulative total approaching 2 trillion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
By then, the country's added gas production capacity is
estimated to rise to 10 billion cubic meters, with a cumulative
total topping 25 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
A senior CNPC official forecasts major breakthroughs in the
expansion of proven gas reserves and production capacity in the
Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region, the Tarim Basin and Sichuan
province. The annual gas output should reach 30 billion cubic
meters by 2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said China has huge gas-production potential, and
that through years of vigorous development, three large-scale gas
production areas have taken shape.
</P>
<P>
In the central part of the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region, total
gas reserves of 230 billion cubic meters have been verified. Total
gas reserves of 200 billion cubic meters have also been confirmed
in the eastern part of Sichuan, while in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region total gas reserves of 160 billion cubic meters
have been located, in addition to the discovery of a group of new
gas-bearing geological structures.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in the Sebei area of northwest China's Qinghai
Province, a large gas field with proven reserves of 50 billion
cubic meters has been identified.
</P>
<P>
Along with domestic gas exploration, active efforts are
underway to utilize the gas resources of neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
In central Asia, China has joined an international gas
exploration project planning the construction of a long-distance
gas pipeline running through China and the Korean Peninsula to
Japan. This project could provide China with a gas supply of 25
billion cubic meters a year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a joint venture with Russia for gas exploration in
eastern Siberia should deliver 25 billion cubic meters of gas to
China annually.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, pipelines running across China will take
shape, which will effectively ease shortage in many cities, the
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets UN Human Rights High Commissioner  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the meeting, Jiang briefed the guests on China's efforts
to combat the severe flooding this summer. In its battle against
the floods, the Chinese government placed the safety of the
people's lives ahead of all else. "We have guaranteed that
residents in the flooded areas have food, clean water, lodging,
and medical services, and that the students in these areas can go
to school," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the loss of life and property was reduced to a
minimum thanks to the efforts made by governments at all levels.
</P>
<P>
The floods of 1931 were much smaller than this year's, but
"they, however, claimed 140,000 lives, which shows a sharply
different historic picture than this year," Jiang said. "It is
also a reflection that only in New China can human rights be
promoted and protected," he added.
</P>
<P>
During China's anti-flood struggle, the international community
gave China tremendous support, Jiang said. A great number of
state and government leaders, international organizations,
enterprises and individuals sent mail and telegrams to the Chinese
government to express their sympathy. They also donated money and
materials for China, showing lofty humanitarianism and deep
friendship to the Chinese people, he said. Their action has
greatly encouraged the strength of the Chinese people and strongly
supported their flood-fighting efforts, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his sincere gratitude and high respect for all
these supporters on behalf of the Chinese government and people.
</P>
<P>
Robinson expressed her sympathy for the losses caused by the
flooding. She said the Chinese people had fought bravely against
the floods under the leadership of President Jiang and the central
government.
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that she appreciates the coherence and
resolve shown by the Chinese people in overcoming difficulties and
calamities. "This is also a reflection of the care of the Chinese
government on human rights," she said, adding that she believes
the Chinese government and people can win a final victory in its
flood-fighting efforts and post-flood reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Jiang also briefed the guests on China's
religious policy and political and economic conditions in the
Tibet Autonomous Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
