<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Up 53.1 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
surged 53.1 percent in July from a year earlier to 1,350.6 billion
yen (about 9.6 billion U.S. dollars), marking the 16th straight
monthly increase, the Japanese Finance Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in goods and services trade jumped 94.6 percent to
901.4 billion yen (about 6.4 billion dollars), the ministry said
in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus in merchandise trade for the reporting month
rose 39.9 percent to 1474.8 billion yen (about 10.5 billion
dollars), with exports up 5.9 percent to 4,403.3 billion yen
(about 31.3 billion dollars) and imports down 5.6 percent to
2928.6 billion yen (about 20.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Although imports from the United States rose 0.9 percent, those
from Japan's Asian neighbors, the 15-member European Union (EU)
and the Middle East slipped 7.0 percent, 9.8 percent and 11.6
percent respectively, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In services trade, Japan posted a deficit of 573.3 billion yen
(about 4.1 billion dollars), down from a deficit of 591.1 billion
yen (about 4.2 billion dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The current account measures the flow of goods and services, as
well as investment income and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen averaged 140.73 to the U.S. dollar in July,
down 22 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
