<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DRC Rebels Should Be Included in Peace Talks: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfread Nzo said Monday that peace efforts in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) would have to involve the
rebels who were trying to overthrow the government of President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Nzo made the remarks in the northern Mauritius resort of Grand
Baie, where the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
started its annual summit on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no other way. I don't think it is going to help
to insist there is no rebel movement," South African Press
Association quoted Nzo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The DRC is insisting the uprising in the country is almost
solely the work of Rwandan and Ugandan forces and that the rebels
be excluded from any cease-fire negotiations.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela, who is chairing the
SADC summit, told reporters that Rwandan and Ugandan delegations
had arrived in Mauritius and would be invited to join the summit
session dealing with the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Both Rwanda and Uganda are not member states of the 14-member
of the SADC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
