<HEADLINE> Ugandan Shilling Slides Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Shilling continues to
depreciate against the U.S. Dollar even after the intervention of the
Bank of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
It slid to a record low of between 1,290 to 1,305 shillings per
Dollar over the weekend, the New Vision paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five months, the Shilling has substantially faY95RkV,k$]4e Doll
ar with selling quotations hiking from 1,160
Shillings in February to 1,260 Shillings in July. It plummeted to
over 1,300 Shillings per Dollar as the situation is getting out of
control, one dealer was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sharp fall of Shilling is blamed on the decrease of coffee
exports and the intensified warfare in neighboring Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The value of coffee exported in the last 11 months has dropped to
258.4 million Dollars from 336.5 million Dollars for the same period
during the 1996/1997 coffee season.
</P>
<P>
This 1997/1998 coffee season, which is coming to an end, worsens the
situation because upcountry coffee growers prefer holding stock to
banking the money. This also contributes to the fall of coffee
exports which account for 55 to 60 percent of the country's
foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the war in DRC also leads to the weakening of the
Ugandan currency. The intensification of the war has scared tourists
away and investors are yanking more Dollars out of the region for
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Ulrike Wilson, the outgoing resident representative of the
International Monetary Fund, however, holds a different view, saying
that the exchange rates are changing worldwide because of crises in
Russia, Latin America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
This is a global trend and should not be considered regionally,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
