<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Delays Release of New Currency for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Uganda will postpone
the release of a 20,000 shilling note to next year due to
security considerations.
</P>
<P>
The bank wants the new note to possess special security
features against forgery, an official with the financial
institution was quoted by the East African weekly as saying
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Counterfeit notes of 10,000- and 5,000-shilling denominations
have been found in circulation and therefore the new note will be
released with greatest care, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Secretary to the Treasury Tumusiime Mutebile said
he ordered the central bank to introduce a 20,000 shilling note
as a matter of urgency. The government was also considering
introducing 50,000 shilling notes, he added.
</P>
<P>
Radio Uganda launched a special program to warn people about
the counterfeit notes because many fake notes have been found in
circulation.
</P>
<P>
Several people illegally operating money-making machines have
so far been arrested, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
