<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, September 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Air Canada passengers could take flight as soon as
Monday, provided the airline's pilots vote this weekend to ratify
the deal that brought an end to the nine-day strike.
</P>
<P>
"There may be a few flights on Monday," Air Canada spokesman
John Hamilton was quoted as saying by the local media Sunday.
Meanwhile, he also said that although international flights may
take a few more days than domestic ones to get back on course, it
should be business as usual for all services by Thursday or
Friday. (Canada-Airline-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- "Unemployment, like a time bomb, is exploding in the
Czech Republic," claimed Czech Prime Minister Milos Zeman recently.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment in August this year reached 320,000, a record of
6.4 percent since the country started reforms towards a market
economy in 1990. However, local economists expect unemployment to
continue increasing in the near future, and expect a rate of 7
percent by the end of the year, 8.4 percent next year and more
than 10 percent by year 2000. (Czech Republic-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- At least four people were killed and dozens of
others injured when a bus collided with a pick-up car on Sunday in
Serang, about 70 kilometers west of Jakarta, Antara News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bus heading to Serang from Jakarta was overtaking a city
transport van when the car suddenly appeared from the opposite
direction, making the collision inevitable, said the report.
(Indonesia-Accident) 
</P>
</TEXT>
