<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Export Insurance Firm Blacklists Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South African exporters to
Kenya will have to pay higher premium for credit insurance as
Kenya is now regarded as a high risk destination.
</P>
<P>
With a high risk rating, Kenya can expect goods from South
Africa to either cost more or reduce in volume, local analysts
warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to charge higher premiums was announced last week
by the South Africa-based Credit Guarantee Insurance Corporation
of Africa, citing Kenya's poor economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The move has drawn criticism from Kenya's Export Promotion
Council, which last month held an one-week "Kenya in South
Africa" trade exhibition in Johannesburg, the East African, a
regional weekly newspaper, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deputy director of the council, Zachary Gichohi, said the
move smacked of "business politics" and was not based on present
economic realities.
</P>
<P>
However, Credit Insurance Corporation, a South African export
insurance company, which insures payments for goods exported to
Kenya by South African companies, now also ranks Kenya as a
high-risk destination for goods.
</P>
<P>
Credit guarantee insurance enables exporters to claim
compensation from an insurer if exported goods are not paid for
by the importer. Premiums depend on the perception of risk in the
importing country.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has grown steadily over the past five years to
become Kenya's leading investor from Africa. The value of its
exports to Kenya, including household utilities, textiles,
foodstuff, wines and beer, has trebled to 20 billion Shillings
(333 million U.S. Dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is also South Africa's biggest trading partner in
sub-Saharan Africa outside the 14-member Southern African
Development Community. Its exports to South Africa stand at 1.2
billion Shillings ( 20 million Dollars), comprising mainly tea,
horticultural produce and soda ash.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan exporters have complained for years about stiff tariff
and non-tariff barriers set up by South Africa to Kenya. A series
of negotiations over how to remove these barriers have been held
between the two governments since last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Mbeya Region Aims at Expanding Coffee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Mbeya Region, a major
coffee producer in Tanzania, has come up with an ambitious plan to
drastically increase its output of the cash crop.
</P>
<P>
The region plans to plant 2.5 million coffee seedlings in
1998/99 season, compared with 425,000 last season and 63,000 in 1995,
and raise the output of a tree from quarter of a kilogram to between
one and two kilograms, Daily News reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Strategies laid to attain the goal include distribution of
quality seedlings, proper nursing of trees and enhancing extended
services, the local paper quoted the Regional Commissioner Basil
Pesambili Mramba as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We want our people here to consider coffee as their main survival
crop," he said, adding that farmers used to regard maize as the
mainstay cash crop.
</P>
<P>
The regional commissioner has also acknowledged problems in the
coffee industry, such as the violation of purchasing regulations by
private buyers and the decline in coffee quality.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's coffee is mainly produced in Arusha and Kilimanjaro
regions in the north and Mbeya in the southwest. Coffee export
earnings during 1995-1997 totaled 120 million U.S. Dollars and
accounted for 15 percent of all commodity exports, statistics
indicated.
</P>
<P>
The output and quality of coffee, however, have both declined in
recent years due to aging trees, lack of farmer education, low use of
fertilizer, poor processing and high labor input, said Leslie Omari,
managing director of state-run Tanzanian Coffee Board.
</P>
<P>
At an annual coffee industry conference in Arusha, President
Benjamin Mkapa challenged the country's coffee growers to double
production within five years, promising full government support for
efforts to reverse successive years of declining yields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
