<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Tourism Set to Pick up After Bad Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tourism industry,
the country's top foreign exchange earner, is on the road to
recovery after a slump last year.
</P>
<P>
The averaged hotel occupancy rate at the Coast, where receives
more than 70 percent of visitors annually, rose to estimated 45
percent last month from 37 percent in July and 24 percent in
June, the East African reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The (tourism) industry is on the path to recovery," Edgar
Francula, the regional manager of the Touristic Union
International (TUI) which is a leading tour operator in Europe,
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said forecasts for tourism in the winter season, which
begins in November, appear very promising.
</P>
<P>
Charter flights to Kenya were expected to double by November
when bookings were also expected to double, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
The advertizing campaign by the Kenya Tourism Board (KTB) in
Europe appeared to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
KTB Chairman Eliud Mahihu said the board placed advertisements
in 35 travel magazines with a readership of over 45 million in
Europe only last month.
</P>
<P>
Tourism nearly came to a standstill last year following the
August eruption of tribal clashes in Mombasa, the capital city of
the Coast Province. About 60,000 hotel workers were laid off
during the slump. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
