<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 08:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Agricultural Cooperaton with Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Jordanian Minister of
Agriculture Moghem al-Kharaisha has called on Jordanian and
Lebanese agricultural sectors to profit from each other and not
compete, the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kharaisha was here to attend the 12th summit of the executive
committee of the Arab Organization for Agricultural Development
which opened on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the two-day conference, he said that Lebanese
and Jordanian agriculture sectors should complement each other.
</P>
<P>
"We have different timetables of production in agriculture and
grow different varieties of fruits and vegetables. We therefore
should find no difficulties in trading with each other," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan imports 30,000 tons of Lebanese food while Lebanon
imports 51,000 tons of food from Jordan each year.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian minister downplayed the border incident last
month when more than 1,000 tons of Lebanese potatoes were stopped
at the Jordanian border for Jordanian officials claimed they fell
below quality standards.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanese farmers believe the Jordanian action was in
response to Lebanon's refusal to accept its watermelons in May.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed an agreement to exchange
Jordanian fruits and vegetables for Lebanon's potatoes early this
year.
</P>
<P>
Kharaisha blamed the two incidents on traders from both
countries, saying they did not respect agricultural calendar nor
the quantities and quality set by the two governments.
</P>
<P>
He called on the agricultural sectors in both countries to
further boost cooperation and trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
