<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Investments in Jordan's tourism are expected to reach
600 million Jordanian dinars (about 847 million U.S. dollars) by
the end of 2000, the Jordan Times newspaper said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Tourism and Antiquities Akil Beltaji said that the
unique tourism characteristics in Jordan, represented by the Dead
Sea and some biblical sites, help boost the investment.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A number of Jordanian companies have secured another
21 million dollars worth of contracts with Iraq under the U.N.
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said that under the 13 new contracts, Jordan
will supply Iraq with soap, vegetable oil and medicine.
</P>
<P>
With the new contracts, Jordan's relevant incomes have reached
more than 350 million dollars since the deal was put into force in
December 1996 to allow Iraq to sell limited amount of oil to buy
food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian exports to Saudi Arabia in the first half of
this year reached 45.3 million dinars (about 63.9 million
dollars), Jordan`s Arabic daily Ad Dustour said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted government resources as saying that Jordanian
exports to Saudi Arabia were recorded at 70 million dollars in
1995 and 130 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The National Bank of Kuwait (NBK) announced
Sunday that its services are available on Internet and clients
will be furnished with the most up-to-date and fastest techniques
of services.
</P>
<P>
General Director of the banking group services Adel Abdel
Wahab Al-Majed said that the NBK clients, who have already enjoyed
the telephone and computer convenience, can start conducting
banking operations, such as account transfers, cancellation of
payment orders and disclosure of all accounts via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
A client can directly contact the employee responsible for his
accounts via e-mail, according to the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Encouraging the clients to use the Internet, the NBK has
decided to cut service fees by 50 percent on the web operations,
Al-Majed said.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The largest bromine factory in Jordan will be set up
by the Jordan Potash Company and the Albemarle Company of the
U.S..
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company will offer 40 percent of the total 120 million
dollars of investments and the rest will be raised through foreign
loans, Minister of Information Nasir Judeh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
