<HEADLINE> Uganda's Illiteracy Rate Down by 22 Percent: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's illiteracy rate has
fallen by 22 percent over the past few years as a result of
the Universal Primary Education (UPE), a senior official said over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Hajat Bbumba, the Minister of State for Economic Monitoring in the
President's Office, made the remarks at the opening ceremony of a
Madrasa Resource Center (MRC) in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The government is looking several decades ahead and that is why it
has invested so much in the eReation sector, she said.
</P>
<P>
The MRC is one of the projects of the Agakhan Development
Network which started in 1967 and operates in 11 countries
including Uganda. Through its early childhood development
programs, the Agakhan Foundation set up the resource centers to
train pre-school childre 67d their teachers.
</P>
<P>
The program started in Uganda in 1993 and an estimated 5,000
children are to benefit from it. Some 28 Ugandan schools are now
under the program and the number is expected to reach 50, the
official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
