<HEADLINE> 2000 Games Plans on Target, Says Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia Tuesday rolls
into the final two years of preparations for the 2000 Sydney
Olympic Games with the construction of venues on target.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony for the Games is scheduled for September
15, 2000, but officials admitted to some nerves as the great
event draws near.
</P>
<P>
"I hesitate to say we're positioned well because as soon as
you start thinking you're on top of this, you'll stuff it up for
sure," Michael Knight, the Olympics Minister and president of the
Sydney Games organising committee (SOCOG) was quoted as saying in
Monday's Sydney Morning Herald newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Games organisers last month released ticketing details, with
more than 9.6 million tickets available and prices ranging from
as little to A$10 (6 U.S. dollars) up to A$1,382 for premium
seats at the opening and closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
Tickets will go on sale by random ballot in mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Most of the other big issues for organisers, such as stadium
construction, accommodation and sponsorship, are reported to be
under control.
</P>
<P>
A number of venues for the Games have already been completed,
while all but two -- tennis and a second water polo centre -- are
under construction.
</P>
<P>
The last venue is expected to be completed in early 2000, the
Herald said.
</P>
<P>
The key works still under construction include the main
stadium at Homebush Bay, scheduled to open next March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
