<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Passes 1999 State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Following days of
wrangling, Israeli cabinet on Sunday night passed with a majority
state budget for 1999 featuring overall spending cut but defense
outlays rise.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of the 17 ministers voted in favor of the budget
proposal, two were against and one abstained, Radio reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
This marked another success for Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, who had persuaded his cabinet to approve the budget
proposal prepared by Finance Minister Ya'akov Neeman.
</P>
<P>
The review of the 1999 budget proposal, which plans a overall
cut and an increase in defense spending for the first time in 10
years, began last week, with 11 ministers being reported to have
opposed the program at the time.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Neeman met with budget opponents over the past
week and managed to piece together a larger-than-expected majority
for the plan.
</P>
<P>
The two said at a news conference after the vote that the
majority was attained by redistributing budget cuts among the
various ministries, and that overall spending will not be higher
than planned.
</P>
<P>
The defense budget, the core of the contention, obtained an
increase of 100 million shekels (about 26 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said defense spending did not rise as much as he
would like, but "it heralds a multi-year increase in
strategic-defense spending."
</P>
<P>
The government has agreed on a 10-year plan meant to increase
defense spending incrementally, he added.
</P>
<P>
Most of the defense budget increase will be used to buy arms,
including jet fighters and combat helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 07:43 </DATE_TIME>
