<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Waters Recede in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Flood waters along the
mainstream of the Songhua River in northeast China and throughout
the river basin continue to recede slowly.
</P>
<P>
The current water level at Harbin, capital of Heilongjiang
Province, is 1.63 meters lower than the highest level during the
summer flood season, but nonetheless remains above the danger mark.
</P>
<P>
Local water conservancy experts predict the water level will
remain above the danger mark for another 20 days. More than
100,000 people in Heilongjiang monitor levees on a 24-hr basis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, water levels along the Nenjiang and Western Liaohe
rivers in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have returned to
normal. Local residents in the areas are currently repairing
projects and rebuilding their homes.
</P>
<P>
The regional Civil Affairs Department has distributed 46.5
million yuan to help homeless flood victims rebuild houses. On
average, each household have got 1,000 yuan to build a new room
before winter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Nets 11.6 Million Dollars From Tax Evaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A crackdown on tax evaders
in Kenya's construction industry has netted the east African
country 700 million Shillings (11.6 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Income Tax Department is also expected to raise about 1.5
billion Shillings (25 million Dollars) from 20 large contractors
and 50 firms, which have long evaded the tax man, the East African
weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The tax audit by the Kenya Revenue Authority revealed that the
32 companies it examined, which included a foreign firm that has
been in Kenya for more than 10 years, have recorded losses every
year.
</P>
<P>
The result alerted the tax authorities to the possibility of
major loopholes that the construction industry, with more than 30
billion Shillings (50 million Dollars) of turnover a year, is used
to avoid paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
Another audit carried out on 38 professional firms revealed
that about 60 percent of them had no files at the Income Tax
Department. Another 25 percent had files but either failed to
file returns or did not provide complete information.
</P>
<P>
Only about 15 percent fully satisfied the conditions set by
the local Income Tax Department, the weekly said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
