<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Wine Exports Hit 50M U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's wine
industry is flourishing with the value of total wine exports
passing the total imported for the first time in the year ending
June 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to an annual report issued here Monday by the Wine
Institute of New Zealand, the value of total wine exports in the
year hit 97.6 million NZ dollars (about 50 million U.S. dollars),
well up from 75.8 million NZ dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the value of total wine imports in the year was 93.4
million NZ dollars (47.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's major export market is Britain where sales of New
Zealand wines have doubled in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Other major importers of New Zealand wines include Australia,
the United States, Japan, the Netherlands, Canada, Germany, Sweden
and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Wine imports into New Zealand mainly come from Australia, Spain
and France.
</P>
<P>
Wine Institute president Ross Spence said that the perception
of New Zealand wines in Britain is very high. The institute has
set up an office there to market the products of New Zealand's
wine industry.
</P>
<P>
An indicator of the value put on New Zealand wines in Britain
was that the average price was 17.13 NZ dollars, higher than the
price of an average-priced bottle from Australia, the United
States, France and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the annual report, more growth in New Zealand's
wine industry is expected. The country recently has 7,943 hectares
of grape vineyards, and that figure is expected to increase to
8,716 hectares by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
