<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Proposes Libyan-Dutch Accord on Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League chief Esmat
Abdel Meguid has proposed that Libya and the Netherlands sign a
pre-trial agreement spelling out details surrounding the
prosecution of the Libyan suspects in the Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
Libya has rejected a new U.S.-British decision to accept the
trial in the Hague before Scottish judges, citing it did not
ensure the safety of the accused during transit and after the
trial should they be convicted.
</P>
<P>
Two Libyans were accused of blowing up a Pan Am plane in 1988
over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people. The U.S. and Britain
had been demanding extradition of the Libyans to either of them,
but lately changed their mind in order to get a speedy trial.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that their offer is unnegotiatable. But the Arabs
are more sympathetic to the Libyan stand at procedural detailed
should be worked out before the suspected are handed over for
trial.
</P>
<P>
"The Libyan and Dutch governments should sign an agreement to
clarify all the issues pending in the Lockerbie case and in which
the suspects will stand trial in the Hague under Scottish law,"
said Abdel Meguid, quoted by Egyptian Gazette Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal will be a tool aimed at pushing things forward
concerning Lockerbie," he said following separate meetings with
the British Ambassador to Egypt David Blatherwick, and the Libyan
delegate to the AL, Salma Rashed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed last week his support for Libya's request for
"guarantees" on the fate of the men.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development Sunday, Libya decided to disband its
Ministry of Promoting Arab Unity in the coming few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency quoted informed Libyan sources as
explaining the decision as in line with Libya's increasing
assertion of its African affiliation.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that Libya is taking the step to
protest Arab failure to have the seven-year-old United Nations
embargo against the Afro-Arab country lifted.
</P>
<P>
In a recent TV interview, Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi has
rapped Arab countries for not showing strong enough support to
Libya, while praising the Organization of African Unity for
backing its demand for lifting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed air, arms and diplomatic embargo on the
country in 1992 after Libya failed to hand over the two suspects
in the Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
Arab foreign ministers are to meet here Wednesday to study the
new developments of the Lockerbie issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
