<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-borne Diseases Spreading in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Diarrhea and other water-borne
diseases are spreading fast among the flood-affected people
throughout Bangladesh as flood waters are receding, a major
English newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 209,981 people have been attacked by diarrheal
diseases in 47 flood-hit districts since July 15, and 174 of them
died, The Independent daily quoted an official in charge of the
central control room of the Health Directorate as saying.
</P>
<P>
Over 4,000 medical teams with 1,998 doctors are working in the
flood-affected areas to treat patients and control the spread of
diseases. In addition to hundreds of existing health centers, 80
temporary treatment camps have also been set up in the vulnerable
areas, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The public health departments are also providing the flood
victims with water purifying tablets, oral saline packets,
tetracycline capsules, intravenous fluid, and other emergency
medicine for common diseases.
</P>
<P>
Besides diarrheal diseases, other diseases like acute
respiratory track infection, pneumonia, dysentery, abdominal pain,
scabies, conjunctivitis and jaundice are also spreading quickly
among the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Children are falling prey to various ailments due to a lack of
pure drinking water, inadequate food and a lack of proper hygienic
conditions in the relief centers.
</P>
<P>
About 37,000 diarrheal patients were treated at the hospital
attached to the International Center for Diarrheal Diseases and
Research in Bangladesh since July 18 when the hospital began to
experience the pressure of the patients, according to the center.
</P>
<P>
The center, which used to treat 200 to 250 patients a day on
average, is now attending 600 to 700 patients daily.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing deluge which began to hit Bangladesh in early July
has so far hit two-thirds of the country's territory and left
about 900 people dead and millions of others homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
