<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Tighten Control on Guest Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Fayez
Tarawneh has pledged to tighten control over the 350,000 foreign
workers in Jordan, mainly Egyptians, Iraqis and Syrians, the
Jordan Times newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister promised to look into all means of
controlling the local labor market and preventing foreigners from
working illegally at the expense of Jordanians, the paper quoted a
government source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh stressed the need to reduce the number of foreign
laborers in Jordan who work mainly in agriculture and
construction sectors, but he steered away from saying how he
would achieve this politically sensitive goal.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Minister of Labor Mohammad Mahdi Farhan
told the press that the ministry was considering to add new jobs
to a list of occupations that non-Jordanians are not allowed to
take as well as to decrease the number of work permits issued to
guest workers in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
By these measures, the ministry intended to make vacancy and
help unemployed Jordanians get jobs.
</P>
<P>
Current regulations bar guest workers from filling 15 kinds of
positions, which include jobs in accountancy, teaching and office
work. Official figures showed that only 50,000 out of the 350,000
foreign laborers have valid work permits.
</P>
<P>
Non-Jordanians, whether with or without work permits, are easy
to be hired in comparison with Jordanians, because employers can
give them lower wages and do not have to pay for their health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources placed the current number of unemployed
Jordanians at about 1.2 million, or 26 percent of its 4.6 million
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
