<HEADLINE> Girl-Trafficking Gang Leader Arrested in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Nepali police have arrested
a gang leader involved in girl-trafficking in different parts of
the country, The Kathmandu Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Krishna Pariyar, 27, was arrested along with his 17-year-old
brother Bishnu Pariyar after a girl, sold by them to Bombay, India
was rescued, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Krishna Pariyar, a native Nepali, had confessed that his gang
had sold 12 girls to a brothel in Bombay. He also said he had been
engaged in girl-trafficking for the past six years with his
offices in different parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that about 5,000 to 7,000 Nepalese women and
girls are trafficked every year through the 1,750-kilometer-long
open Indo-Nepal border.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 200,000 Nepalese women and children who have been
trafficked to India are forced into prostitution, the State of the
Rights of the Child in Nepal 1998 said.
</P>
<P>
A survey found that poverty, unemployment and ignorance are the
major factors contributing to the commercial sexual exploitation
of women and children in Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
