<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Agriculture Bank Asked to Raise Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has suggested
Thailand's Bank of Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives
(BAAC) raise interest rates in order to reflect the cost of
funding, the Nation newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Ennoo Seusawan, executive vice-president of the BAAC,
the newspaper said the move also aims to avoid market distortion.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate hike recommendation came after
representatives of the World Bank recently completed a BAAC
performance review.
</P>
<P>
To comply with lending discipline, the BAAC will raise interest
rates on selected lending portfolios to market rates, Ennoo said.
</P>
<P>
However, the BAAC will maintain low interest rates on farmers'
or small agricultural cooperatives' loans in order to keep their
interest burdens at a minimum, he added.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the average BAAC interest rate is 11.5 percent on
loans up to 60,000 baht (1,500 U.S. dollars). On loans worth more
than 60,000 baht, the bank will charge between 12.5 and 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
According to Ennoo, the World Bank also suggested the BAAC
improve loan-loss reserves by shortening the bank-reserve
requirement period for bad debts.
</P>
<P>
The BAAC will cut 10-year full reserves to five years in order
to strengthen its accounting practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
To increase its lending, the BAAC will recapitalize up to 20
billion baht (500 million dollars) from the current 9.6 billion
baht (240 million dollars) within the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
