<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government to Start Austerity Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina has approved a circular on an austerity drive, the
Independent daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The austerity drive aims to cut down non-essential expenditure
in all government offices and divert the funds for relief and
post-flood reconstruction, the newspaper said. The Finance
Ministry will issue the circular soon.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Hasina minister called for observing austerity
nation-wide, including in public and private offices, to deal with
the problems arising out of the two-month-long flooding.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kibria said the money saved would be
used for the gigantic task of rehabilitation in the flooding
areas.
</P>
<P>
Under the austerity plan, he said, extravagant spending on
luxury affairs would be discouraged.
</P>
<P>
Contingency funds of all ministries would be cut down, use of
fuel for office transports and foreign travels by ministers and
bureaucrats would be curtailed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister herself canceled a plan to attend the
Non-Aligned Movement summit in South Africa early this month, and
her trips to Malaysia, Brunei and Vietnam scheduled for early next
month were also canceled.
</P>
<P>
There are many ways to avoid wasteful expenditure, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The current floods have hit two-thirds of the country's total
area, affecting about 30 million people in 47 of the 64 districts,
and the death toll has risen to nearly 900. 
</P>
</TEXT>
