<HEADLINE> One Percent of Indians Infected With HIV: Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- One out of every 100
persons in India is infected with HIV which causes AIDS, according
to recent countrywide official surveys.
</P>
<P>
A senior official at the Health Ministry, requesting anonymity,
said the situation in the country was serious. "Several
top-ranking people are seeking help for their relatives. But no
one wants to come forward and say that AIDS is affecting our near
and dear ones."
</P>
<P>
Prasada Rao, a project director of the National AIDS Program,
said: "The infection rate has touched one percent. Beyond this,
the spread is extremely fast."
</P>
<P>
If the spread was not arrested at this stage, it might result
in an Africa-like situation, where young earning members of
households were wiped off by the virus, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, the Indian government initiated a program in a
bid to arrest the spread of the AIDS virus, and the National AIDS
Control Program was launched in April 1987.
</P>
<P>
A separate wing, called the National AIDS Control Organization,
was set up soon after. It received a soft loan of 84 million U.S.
dollars from the World Bank for the period of 1992-97.
</P>
<P>
Since then, however, cases of HIV infection have grown rapidly,
with the virus penetrating the general population gradually. It
first entered the high-risk segments such as sex-workers and
intra-venous drug-users. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Russian Crisis Moderately Hits Kazak Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia's financial crisis
that has shaken the world market has moderately hit
Kazakhstan. Inflation in the Central Asian country is estimated to
be 6 to 7 percent, low enough to keep its economy going.
</P>
<P>
Still closely linked to the Russian market, Kazakhstan sells
one third of its exports to Russia. But its currency, tenge,
devalued only 3.94 percent in the first eight months of 1998 as
the Russian ruble depreciated 200 percent in one month.
</P>
<P>
A strong financial system helps the country avoid a
Russian-style crisis, said Alievich Dzhandosov, chairman of the
National Bank of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
He said Kazakhstan has built a financial structure independent
of the Russian system, which was further improved with reforms in
recent years. Now the country's foreign exchange reserves stand at
two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the Russian crisis does affect the Kazak economy
moderately. Since the end of August, Russians thronged into
Kazakhstan to use rubles to buy tenges at extremely low prices,
and then resold tenges for U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the value of the tenge started to slip, and the
rate between it and the dollar touched 100 to one in the worst
days.
</P>
<P>
Along with the depreciation of the currency, commodities prices
began soaring, with sugar, rice and other daily necessities up by
almost 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In fear of further price hikes, poor people started to buy
foods in panic while the rich bought the dollar and the Deutsch
mark.
</P>
<P>
In Alma-Ata, banks as well as peddlers in these days rushed for
dollars, sending its rate to one against 90 tenge, an increase of
15 percent. Meanwhile, prices in Alma-Ata were raised by a flat 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
To control the situation, the Kazak government and the central
bank have demanded all commercial banks to stop speculation on the
currency market, and also set a ceiling of one dollar to 85 tenges.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government adopted emergency measures to slash
budget spending by 60 billion tenges.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts have helped stablize the financial
situation. Dzhandosov, the central banker, said confidently that
the Russian crisis does strike Kazakhstan, but not with much
effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholarships Fail to Help Thai Children Stay at School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A free scholarship program
launched by the Thai government has failed to keep economic
crisis-affected children at school, the Bangkok Post reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kanuengnit Klinmuang, a counselor with the Islamic College of
Thailand in Bangkok, said at least 15 students at the college had
dropped out this term and more were likely to follow.
</P>
<P>
The counselor, who is responsible for the school's
scholarships, said the school badly needed funds since needy
students now had only 200,000 baht (5,000 U.S. dollars) in
donation to help them.
</P>
<P>
The scholarship program was approved by the cabinet in June,
about one month after the first term began. It is funded by a one
billion-baht (25 million dollars) loan from the Asian Development
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, a primary school student should get 4,000
baht (100 dollars) and a lower secondary school student 5,000 bath
(125 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some school administrators say the program is likely to fail
because it has come too late. Those children who have left schools
are unlikely to return since they don't want to catch up on
classes missed. The program only covers one year of education.
</P>
<P>
So far, there have been an estimated 200,000 dropouts
nationwide, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
