<HEADLINE> Stolen Passports of Nepali Delegation Found in SAfrica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 14 (Xinhua) -- All the 21 diplomatic
passports including that of Nepali Prime Minister Girija Prasad
Koirala which were stolen early this month in South Africa have
been found and are on their way to Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
The South African government had informed the Nepali Foreign
Ministry about the recovery of the passports lost at the Durban
International Airport of South Africa, a Nepali journalist said
Monday. His passport was stolen as well.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali delegation found the bag containing the passports
stolen when it was leaving Durban for Johannesburg on September 4
after attending the 12th Summit of the Non-Aligned Movement held
on September 2-3, said the journalist who accompanied the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the advice of the South African Foreign
Ministry, Nepali Foreign Ministry officials in the delegation
wrote letters of certificate to serve as provisional passports.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of passports, the delegation could not exchange
its traveler's checks in Johannesburg and Dubai, the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
But the Qatar government made all the arrangements when the
Nepali delegation arrived on September 5-8 for an official visit.
</P>
<P>
The delegation returned home on September 8 without passports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
