<HEADLINE> Air Canada Set to Take off Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada passengers could
take flight as soon as Monday, provided the airline's pilots vote
this weekend to ratify the deal that brought an end to the
nine-day strike.
</P>
<P>
"There may be a few flights on Monday," Air Canada spokesman
John Hamilton was quoted as saying by the local media Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But while Hamilton said international flights may take a few
more days than domestic ones to get back on course, it should be
business as usual for all services by Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada mechanics were called back to the job Friday,
Hamilton said, making necessary preparations for services to
resume.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada pilots went on strike on September 2. The pilots
are seeking a 12-percent raise spread over two years to their
current average salary of 100,000 Canadian dollars (57,000 U.S.
dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
The company's latest offer was a boost of nine percent over two
years. Air Canada and its 2,100 striking pilots reached an
agreement in principle late Thursday to end the nine-day strike.
</P>
<P>
But Hamilton refused to comment on reports that pilots will get
a 9 percent wage increase over two years. "We agreed with the
union that we wouldn't release it publically until the
ratification is announced Monday," Hamilton said. 
</P>
