<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Buddhist University to Open in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- An international Buddhist
missionary university, the first one in Myanmar to teach Theravada
(Little Vehicle) Buddhism in various languages, will open here in
December this year, according to official religion sources.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the International Theravada Buddhist
Missionary University (ITBMU) is aimed at sharing the genuine
Theravada Buddhism with followers in the world, and studying and
comprehending the canonical texts of the Buddhism which eventually
lead to the purification, perpetuation and propagation of the
Buddha teachings in the world.
</P>
<P>
The university will begin with a one-year diploma course with
different language teachings covering English, Chinese, French,
Japanese, German, Hindu and Arabic. The medium of instruction will
be in English.
</P>
<P>
The subjects to be taught in the university cover theory and
practice of Buddhism, Buddhist culture, history, comparative
studies of religions, Pali and Myanmar languages.
</P>
<P>
Foreign monks, nuns and laypersons, who have passed the
matriculation standard, are allowed to join the university, or
they will have to sit for entrance examinations.
</P>
<P>
Those who complete the initial one-year diploma course are
allowed for further studies for Bachelor, Master and Doctor
degrees of Philosophy in Buddha teaching.
</P>
<P>
A country with a majority of its population (about 89.4
percent) believing in Buddhism, Myanmar had established Buddhist
scripture learning centers and other monastic education schools
long ago.
</P>
<P>
There are two state Buddhist universities in the country, one
in Yangon and the other in Mandalay.
</P>
<P>
For nearly a thousand years, Myanmar has kept Theravada
Buddhism pure and intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
