<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji has said the reconstruction of
flooded areas on the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze River
should be geared to the aim of eliminating future flood threats.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist party of China Central Committee, made the
statement during a tour of Hubei, Jiangxi, Hunan and Sichuan
provinces and Chongqing municipality, areas that were hit by
devastating floods this summer.
</P>
<P>
"The most urgent tasks right now are to make sure that the
people displaced by the floods can survive the winter and to
combine the reconstruction of the flood-hit areas with work to
guard against and prevent future floods," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
-- A commentary frontpaged the daily calling for nationwide
speaking of standard Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing called for greater efforts
to ensure good sanitation conditions and prevent diseases and
epidemics in the flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
During an inspection tour of northeast China's Heilongjiang and
Jilin provinces and northern China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region between September 11 and 13, Li also said that a good job
must be done of rebuilding primary and middle schools destroyed by
floods.
</P>
<P>
-- China's principal economic indexes show an overall rebound
in August, according to a latest State Statistics Bureau report.
</P>
<P>
The report reveals that China generated an industrial added
value of 158.2 billion yuan in August, up 7.9 percent on an annual
basis or 0.3 percentage points higher than that of the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The second China Fair for International Investment and Trade
closed on Saturday with eye-catching results, a senor trade
official said.
</P>
<P>
The five-day event secured commitments worth 14.2 billion
U.S. dollars in the form of foreign investment in 2,766 projects,
according to Wang Shijia, director-general of the Department of
Foreign Investment Administration under the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S.' newly imposed regulation to control Chinese
imports packed in wooden crates is "irrational" and will hinder
bilateral trade relations, argues a Chinese official.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Department officials announced on Friday their intention
to ban untreated solid-wood packaging from Chinese imports to
prevent entrance of Asian long-horned beetles into the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
