<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, IMF Agree on "Flexible" Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) has reached
agreement that the country will maintain a "flexible" interest
rate policy to ward off any speculative attacks against its
currency.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was contained in the final draft of a new
Memorandum of Economic and Financial Policies reached recently
between the Philippines and the IMF, the Today newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the central bank will continue to use
interest rates as tool to address any pressure on the Philippine
peso.
</P>
<P>
This means interest rates will be kept at high levels when the
currency is under speculative attacks as seen last week at the
Philippine Dealing System, the country's electronic currency spot
market.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, however, will not support any move by the central bank
to intervene in the currency market, whether directly or
indirectly.
</P>
<P>
The draft says that foreign exchange must remain
market-determined, a clear statement of policy from the IMF that
foreign exchange controls similar to what Malaysia has adopted
should never be applied by the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying
earlier that the central bank had no plans to bring down further
its overnight interest rates to "normal" levels of 13 percent for
borrowing and 15 percent for lending.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's overnight rates were jacked up by five
percentage points in over two days to 18 percent for borrowing and
20 percent for lending in mid-August when speculators pounced on
the peso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
