<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middlesbrough Beats Tottenham Spurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Two first half goals from
Colombian international Hamilton Ricard and a late one from
Vladimir Kinder helped Middlesbrough beat Tottenham Hotspurs at
the English Premier League on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The victory was also a nice return for Paul Gascoigne, who has
been dropped from Glenn Hoddle's English team for the European
Championship qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
Gascoigne, who spent four seasons with Tottenham from 1988 to
1992, was given a generous reception by the home crowd and he and
Andy Townsend controlled the midfield area.
</P>
<P>
The victory lifted Middlesgrough to sixth place on eight
points Aston Villa lead on 13 points after beating Wimbledon 2-0
on Saturday and have a three-point advantage over Liverpool, who
lost 2-1 at West Ham.
</P>
<P>
Middlesbrough manager Bryan Robson was delighted with a second
successive away win following the midweek victory at Leicester.
</P>
<P>
"That's given us a lot of encouragement," he said, adding that
he was particularly pleased with his newlook central defensive
trio of Gary Pallister, Colin Cooper and Steve Vickers.
</P>
<P>
"The last time we were in the premier league (two seasons ago)
we only won two away games all season but with that backline we
feel we can go away and get results now," said Robson.
</P>
<P>
Ricard's first goal came after 25 minutes. The Colombian
turned Colin Calderwood, slipped the ball to Danish strike
partner Mikkel Beck and raced on to the return before firing low
past Espen Baardsen in the Tottenham goal.
</P>
<P>
Ricard and Beck combined in similar fashion for the second
after 32 minutes. Ricard flicked a throw-in to Beck who headed
the ball across the edge of the penalty area and the Colombian
outpaced Calderwood to lash the bouncing ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
Tottenham, who parted company with Swiss manager Christian
Gross a week ago, had won their last two games, but their best
effort in a sorry first-half performance was a David Ginola free
kick comfortably saved by 'Boro goalkeeper Mark Schwarzer.
</P>
<P>
Middlesbrough continued to create better chances after the
break and Beck twice tested Baardsen with excellent shots from
distance.
</P>
<P>
Slovakian Kinder, who replaced Gascoigne five minutes from
time, made it 3-0 after 87 minutes with a swerving shot that
surprised the otherwise outstanding Baardsen, who could only
fumble it into the net.
</P>
<P>
The closest Tottenham came to scoring was an injury time
header from substitute Chris Armstrong which hit the post.
</P>
<P>
David Pleat, standing in as team manager until Gross's
successor is found, was decidedly unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
"It's disappointing as the two wins in a row had got
everyone's hopes up," he said. "Maybe some our players started
believing their own publicity. We had lots of possession but most
of it was futile." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
