<HEADLINE> Rafter Wins U.S. Open Men's Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Patrick Rafter of Australia
put the crowning touch on an outstanding year Sunday as he
successfully defended his U.S. Open men's title with 6-3, 3-6,
6-2, 6-0 victory over fellow Australian unseeded Mark
Philippoiussis.
</P>
<P>
Rafter took control of the match midway through the third set
when he broke Philippoussis to lead 4-2, and then reeled off 10
consecutive games to clinch the title.
</P>
<P>
Rafter entered the tournament as the hottest player on the
men's tour and he continued his torrid play Sunday in the first
U.S. Open final between two Australians since 1970.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Rafter became the sixth player of the Open
Era to successfully defend his U.S. Open title. He recorded his
sixth tournament title of the year and ran his record to 25-2
since Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, who was seeded third, played masterful tennis and
except for one brief moment in the second set when he faltered
and had his serve broken, was in control for the entire match.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Rafter had six aces and only one double fault, with
39 winners against only five unforced errors. He forced 20 break
points and was successful on six.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis, playing in his first Grand Slam final, could
not capitalize on his usually powerful serve. He managed only
five aces and committed 13 double faults, the final one coming on
match point. He had 34 winners but made 29 unforced errors.
Philippoussis could force only three break points against Rafter
and was successful on one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
