<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- New Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov stated on
Sunday that he will submit proposals for the new government by the
end of next week.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the NTV Itogi television Primakov said
that he would meet all party factions to discuss the government
formation and submit his proposals to the president by the end of
next week.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the new government must be reorganized by
professionals. Some other Communists could join the Cabinet, but
only if they were professionals, Primakov said.
(Russia-Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Islamic Taliban militia Sunday rejected Iran's
request for tendering an apology and handing over the killers of
nine Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
"We will never tender apology to Iran for the killing of its
diplomats as the Afghan Islamic Emirate is not involved in the
incident," Taliban's envoy in Pakistan, Saeedur Rahman Haqqani
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Iranian diplomats and one reporter went missing when the
Taliban fighters took over the northern Afghan city of
Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the pro-Iranian northern alliance,
early last month.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have been denying Iran's allegations of
abducting these Iranians, announced Wednesday that it had
recovered the bodies of nine Iranian diplomats at the outskirts of
Mazar-e-Sharif. (Taliban-Iran-Apology)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's main political allies,
the Christian Social Union (CDU) party, succeeded in defending its
absolute majority in the local parliamentary election in the
southern German state of Bavaria on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a local vote widely seen as a sentiment test for the German
national elections just two weeks away, the CSU, the Bavarian
sister party of Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU), managed
to win about 53 percent of the vote, almost unchanged from its
showing of 52.8 percent in the 1994 local election, preliminary
computer projections showed.
</P>
<P>
Germany's main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), which
is leading Kohl in popularity polls nationwide, scored only a
little more than 29 percent, down from its 1994 showing of 30
percent, thus failing to orchestrate a major setback for Kohl as
it expected earlier. (Germany-local Election) 
</P>
</TEXT>
