<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> -Sports-U.S. Open-Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hingis, Novotna Win U.S. Open Doubles Title
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Martina Hingis of
Switzerland and Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic beat their
rivals to win the women's doubles title at the U.S. Open tennis
championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hingis became the only fourth woman in history to record a
Grand Slam doubles sweep as she combined with Novotna to oust
Lindsay Davenport of the United States and Natasha Zvereva of
Belarus 6-3, 6-3 in the final.
</P>
<P>
Hingis and Novotna, the top seeds at the Open, earlier won the
French Open and Wimbledon doubles titles. Hingis also teamed with
Mirjana Lucic of Croatia to win the Australian Open doubles
title. Hingis joins Martina Navratilova and Pam Shriver, who won
all four doubles titles in 1984, and Maria Bueno of Brazil, who
won all four with two differenct partners in 1960, as the only
women to sweep the Grand Slam doubles events.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who is ranked No. 1 in the world in both singles and
doubles, and Novotna did not lose a set in winning the title.
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. Open juniors singles titles were settled Sunday
and Australia produced another winner in the girls competition as
second seed Jelena Dokic beat top seed Katarina Srebotnik of
Slovenia 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Dokic did not lose a set in winning five matches en route to
the title. Srebotnik had won the Wimbledon junior championship
and was ranked No. 1 in the world. Dokic won the French Open
junior title.
</P>
<P>
In the boys juniors, 10th seed David Nalbandian of Argentina
upset fourth seed Roger Federer of Switzerland 6-3, 7-5 in the
final.
</P>
<P>
Nalbandian, playing in only his second junior Grand Slam
event, is coached by his father and former ATP player Horatio de
la Pena.Federer won the Wimbledon junior championship this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980914.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Trails Hingis by Only 146 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- When the WTA Tour releases
its weekly rankings Monday, U.S. Open singles champion Lindsay
Davenport of the United States is to trail top-ranked Martina
Hingis of Switzerland by only 146 points.
</P>
<P>
The margin is the closest Davenport has been to the No. 1
ranking. Previously, the closest margin between Hingis and
Davenport was 444 points on August 17 of this year. The largest
margin was 2,356 points in early January.
</P>
<P>
Hingis will have 5,616 points, Davenport 5,470 and number
three Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic 5,063. Hingis won the
Australian Open this year, Novotna took Wimbledon and Davenport
captured the U.S. Open. Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain won the
French Open.
</P>
<P>
This is the first year since 1990 and the only sixth time in
the Open history that four differenct women have won the year's
Grand Slam titles. In 1990, Steffi Graf won the Australian Open,
Monica Seles took the French Open, Martina Navratilova won the
Wimbledon title and Gabriela Sabatini took the U.S. Open
championship.
</P>
<P>
Davenport is only the fourth American-born woman to win the
U.S.Open singles title in the Open Era. She also is the only
third Olympic gold medalist to win the U. S. Open title. And in
addition, Davenport is the only seventh woman in the Open Era to
win the U. S. Open without losing a set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
